00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.960
[Amit Varma]: So, you have Jahangir's minions holding the snake, forcing his mouth open and shoving

00:01:28.960 --> 00:01:30.280
[Amit Varma]: the rabbit inside.

00:01:30.280 --> 00:01:34.480
[Amit Varma]: In the process, the mouth of the hapless snake is torn and it perishes.

00:01:34.480 --> 00:01:39.200
[Amit Varma]: Not the first or last victim of the whims of an autocrat drunk on power.

00:01:39.200 --> 00:01:44.760
[Amit Varma]: And this reminded me of modern times, because we see many of our leaders treat our economy

00:01:44.760 --> 00:01:47.400
[Amit Varma]: just as Jahangir treated that snake.

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:50.120
[Amit Varma]: I wish Jahangir had just left that snake alone.

00:01:50.120 --> 00:01:56.000
[Amit Varma]: The moral of the story, as you would have guessed by now, is this, the snake died.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:03.920
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:04.920
[Unknown]: science.

00:02:04.920 --> 00:02:07.920
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:02:07.920 --> 00:02:10.840
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:02:10.840 --> 00:02:15.760
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Parvati Sharma and we'll be talking about her book, Jahangir, an intimate

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:17.620
[Amit Varma]: portrait of a great Mughal.

00:02:17.620 --> 00:02:22.120
[Amit Varma]: This is not only a serious book of history that contained many insights and TIL moments

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:27.520
[Amit Varma]: for me, but it was also a fantastically entertaining book to read with many moments that made me

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:28.880
[Amit Varma]: laugh out loud.

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:34.280
[Amit Varma]: Also, as much as it is a book of history, it is also a story about people with all their

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:37.440
[Amit Varma]: flaws and insecurities and idiosyncrasies.

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:42.520
[Amit Varma]: It's quite apt to call this, as the subtitle of the book suggests, an intimate portrait,

00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:47.280
[Amit Varma]: because it did feel like I got some insight into Jahangir the man through this book.

00:02:47.280 --> 00:02:50.000
[Amit Varma]: I also have another reason for doing this episode.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:55.560
[Amit Varma]: Every episode of the scene and the unseen through its nearly 150 episode history has

00:02:55.560 --> 00:02:57.080
[Amit Varma]: featured a Verma.

00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:00.040
[Amit Varma]: I've never had a Sharma on the show.

00:03:00.040 --> 00:03:04.440
[Amit Varma]: Like me, are you someone who loves fine art, but can't really afford to have paintings

00:03:04.440 --> 00:03:06.480
[Amit Varma]: by the artists you like hanging on your walls?

00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:07.840
[Amit Varma]: Well, worry no more.

00:03:07.840 --> 00:03:10.440
[Amit Varma]: Head on over to Indiancolors.com.

00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:14.360
[Amit Varma]: Indiancolors is a company that licenses images of the finest modern art from some of the

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:19.240
[Amit Varma]: best artists in India and adapts them into objects of everyday use.

00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:23.560
[Amit Varma]: These include wearable art like stoles and shrugs, home decor like cushion covers and

00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:26.400
[Amit Varma]: table runners, and accessories like tote bags.

00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:31.160
[Amit Varma]: This allows art lovers to actually get fine art into their homes at an accessible price,

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:34.640
[Amit Varma]: and artists get royalties on sales, just like authors do.

00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:38.920
[Amit Varma]: What's more, Indiancolors now has an exciting range of new products, including fridge magnets

00:03:38.920 --> 00:03:43.520
[Amit Varma]: with some stunning motifs, and salad bowls and platters made of mango wood.

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:48.320
[Amit Varma]: Their artists include luminaries like Babu Xavier, Wazvoo x Wazvoo, Brinda Miller, Dilip

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:50.920
[Amit Varma]: Sharma, Shruti Nelson, and Pradeep Mishra.

00:03:50.920 --> 00:03:54.360
[Amit Varma]: They accept bulk orders for corporate and festival gifting, but even if you want to

00:03:54.360 --> 00:03:58.640
[Amit Varma]: buy just for yourself or a friend, head on over to Indiancolors.com.

00:03:58.640 --> 00:04:00.360
[Amit Varma]: That's colors with an O-U.

00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:03.920
[Amit Varma]: And if you want a 20% discount, apply the code IVM20.

00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:06.040
[Amit Varma]: That's IVM for IVM podcast.

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:09.520
[Amit Varma]: IVM20 for a 20% discount at Indiancolors.com.

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:12.920
[Amit Varma]: Parvati, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:04:12.920 --> 00:04:13.920
[Guest]: Thank you very much, Amit.

00:04:13.920 --> 00:04:14.920
[Guest]: It's lovely to be here.

00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:19.120
[Guest]: Glad to be the first Sharma on your show.

00:04:19.120 --> 00:04:22.440
[Guest]: And that story that you told about the snake, I'm glad you picked that.

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:25.560
[Guest]: That was one of my many favorite stories when I was writing this book.

00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:29.840
[Guest]: And people used to get a little worried when they saw me approach, but I just couldn't

00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:30.840
[Guest]: stop telling them.

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:36.400
[Guest]: My Jahangir story is the latest mad thing I had read of this man doing.

00:04:36.400 --> 00:04:39.740
[Guest]: And this was one of my top, top five.

00:04:39.740 --> 00:04:43.440
[Amit Varma]: This is a fantastic story, but there are, like you said, so many fantastic stories.

00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:47.400
[Amit Varma]: And we'll, you know, come back to some of them during our conversation.

00:04:47.400 --> 00:04:53.180
[Amit Varma]: Before we get to ancient times and before we get to Jahangir, let's talk a little bit

00:04:53.180 --> 00:04:54.640
[Amit Varma]: more about yourself.

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:57.800
[Amit Varma]: I've heard you mentioned that you didn't really like history in school.

00:04:57.800 --> 00:05:00.880
[Guest]: I know I won't say I didn't like history in school.

00:05:00.880 --> 00:05:09.280
[Guest]: I think for much of my schooling, I was sort of indifferent to it.

00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:14.760
[Guest]: Really in the sense that it was, it didn't seem to go anywhere or mean anything.

00:05:14.760 --> 00:05:23.960
[Guest]: And it was just these sort of abstractions and these dates and these names, you know,

00:05:23.960 --> 00:05:31.840
[Guest]: and the Mauryas and the Guptas and the Cholas and the Pandyas and the Pallavas and the Rashtrakutas

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:32.840
[Amit Varma]: and the Mughals.

00:05:32.840 --> 00:05:35.840
[Guest]: And a sunny dual would say, Tariq pe Tariq.

00:05:35.840 --> 00:05:37.000
[Guest]: Tariq pe Tariq, yes.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:39.320
[Guest]: None of it added up to anything.

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:46.960
[Guest]: But I think I did begin to enjoy it towards the end, like in my 11th and 12th standard.

00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:50.800
[Guest]: And but even then I didn't, in college I was always drawn towards literature and that's

00:05:50.800 --> 00:05:51.800
[Guest]: what I wanted to study.

00:05:51.800 --> 00:05:58.840
[Guest]: But I think after three years of English, I wanted to do sort of what I thought at the

00:05:58.840 --> 00:06:01.480
[Guest]: time rather naively, real stories.

00:06:01.480 --> 00:06:05.520
[Guest]: You know, I wanted to know the true things.

00:06:05.520 --> 00:06:08.960
[Guest]: So then I went back to studying history.

00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:13.120
[Guest]: And that's when I really began to, you know, began to enjoy it.

00:06:13.120 --> 00:06:16.720
[Guest]: Because I think that sort of the disciplines of literature and history are not very far

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:17.720
[Guest]: apart.

00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:23.400
[Guest]: Some of similar sort of faculties and have similar pleasures.

00:06:23.400 --> 00:06:25.240
[Amit Varma]: And did you always want to be a writer?

00:06:25.240 --> 00:06:29.400
[Guest]: I always wanted to be a writer, yes.

00:06:29.400 --> 00:06:31.120
[Guest]: I don't even know from when.

00:06:31.120 --> 00:06:34.040
[Guest]: I mean, I always wanted to be a writer.

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:36.200
[Guest]: I always wanted to be published.

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:43.360
[Guest]: And as the older I got, and the less published I was, the sadder I became.

00:06:43.360 --> 00:06:49.040
[Guest]: And I remember, you know, I think turning 30, which was also a stressful moment.

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:56.320
[Guest]: And generally bevelling my fate and saying, oh, I will never, never be published.

00:06:56.320 --> 00:07:01.920
[Guest]: And a friend said to me, she said that, you know, if you don't write, what will anyone

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:02.920
[Guest]: publish?

00:07:02.920 --> 00:07:09.800
[Guest]: And then, you know, we were talking earlier about discipline in writing.

00:07:09.800 --> 00:07:14.480
[Guest]: And that's when I started doing this, at her suggestion only, writing every day.

00:07:14.480 --> 00:07:18.440
[Guest]: You just sit and write for one hour every day, or at least sit in front of your computer

00:07:18.440 --> 00:07:21.640
[Guest]: for one hour every day regardless of what comes out.

00:07:21.640 --> 00:07:24.920
[Guest]: And I started doing that like exercise.

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:29.120
[Guest]: And it, you know, it worked because it's like a muscle, you know, you strengthen it the

00:07:29.120 --> 00:07:30.120
[Guest]: more you do it.

00:07:30.120 --> 00:07:37.640
[Guest]: So yeah, so that I think is when I started writing with some kind of plan.

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:43.680
[Guest]: But, but much before that, I mean, from as long back as I can remember, sort of scribbling

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:50.280
[Guest]: away in diaries and things and trying to imitate whatever, whoever I liked at the moment, at

00:07:50.280 --> 00:07:54.640
[Guest]: that time, whichever writer I was reading, I wanted to, you know, be that writer.

00:07:54.640 --> 00:07:55.640
[Amit Varma]: So yeah.

00:07:55.640 --> 00:08:00.520
[Amit Varma]: It sounds very similar to me, I remember when as a kid, I used to read Shakespeare, I had

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:04.600
[Amit Varma]: this brief phase when I tried to write like Shakespeare in that language, which is extremely

00:08:04.600 --> 00:08:07.040
[Amit Varma]: silly and don't try this at home.

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:09.120
[Amit Varma]: And I also was unpublished before 30.

00:08:09.120 --> 00:08:11.800
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting, you know, our mutual friend Manu Pillay was on the show.

00:08:11.800 --> 00:08:13.400
[Guest]: Yes, he's not 30.

00:08:13.400 --> 00:08:16.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, he's just about to turn 30 or turn 30.

00:08:16.600 --> 00:08:20.600
[Amit Varma]: And he mentioned to me while, you know, while we were having coffee before one of his shows,

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:22.800
[Amit Varma]: and it made me very angry, I wanted to punch him.

00:08:22.800 --> 00:08:26.080
[Amit Varma]: He said that, you know, this book has fulfilled an ambition of mine.

00:08:26.080 --> 00:08:27.640
[Amit Varma]: And I said, What is that?

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:31.920
[Amit Varma]: And he said, I wanted to write three books before I was 30.

00:08:31.920 --> 00:08:37.200
[Amit Varma]: And I was like, this kid has barely started shaving and reaching such heights.

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:39.840
[Amit Varma]: But now you also have written many books.

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:43.880
[Amit Varma]: And so to start with, did you you saw yourself as a writer of fiction, right?

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:44.880
[Amit Varma]: Always, yeah.

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:47.240
[Guest]: Yeah, that was what I always wanted to write.

00:08:47.240 --> 00:08:56.920
[Guest]: And it's also what I always enjoyed reading, you know, I loved books and fiction.

00:08:56.920 --> 00:09:00.160
[Guest]: So I wanted to write them.

00:09:00.160 --> 00:09:03.920
[Amit Varma]: Who was who was sort of the writers that you really liked, or the writers that you thought

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:05.600
[Amit Varma]: that you might one day write like?

00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:09.800
[Amit Varma]: I mean, in the sense, that's sort of my space, that kind of thing.

00:09:09.800 --> 00:09:14.680
[Guest]: You know, so like, so every everyone at that moment, whoever it was, so so so like your

00:09:14.680 --> 00:09:23.600
[Guest]: Shakespeare, I also I took on Dostoevsky at the age of I think, 16 or 17, I read Crime

00:09:23.600 --> 00:09:26.360
[Guest]: and Punishment and I didn't like the ending at all.

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:27.360
[Guest]: I was like, what is this?

00:09:27.360 --> 00:09:28.360
[Guest]: I can do better.

00:09:28.360 --> 00:09:29.360
[Unknown]: Did you?

00:09:29.360 --> 00:09:30.360
[Guest]: I rewrote the ending.

00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:33.560
[Amit Varma]: You rewrote the ending of Crime and Punishment.

00:09:33.560 --> 00:09:37.240
[Guest]: So I think the punishment for that was that I was not able to write anything worthwhile

00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:38.240
[Guest]: until I was 30.

00:09:38.240 --> 00:09:43.200
[Guest]: This kind of arrogance should not just go ignored by the universe.

00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:50.080
[Guest]: But, you know, there's some like deep influences, you know, from childhood.

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:52.720
[Guest]: I think I think Roald Dahl was one.

00:09:52.720 --> 00:09:58.680
[Guest]: Something about and even now I think something about just that, that sort of manic flow,

00:09:58.680 --> 00:10:04.240
[Guest]: momentum and energy that he has in all his writing, both for adults and children, is

00:10:04.240 --> 00:10:06.480
[Guest]: something that I aspire to.

00:10:06.480 --> 00:10:07.480
[Guest]: P.G.

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:14.400
[Guest]: Woodhouse, of course, I remember I think also sometime in college reading The God of Small

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:18.800
[Guest]: Things and really being completely blown away by it.

00:10:18.800 --> 00:10:25.160
[Guest]: I think I started it something after dinner and I read the whole night.

00:10:25.160 --> 00:10:32.920
[Guest]: And I think part of the reason it was the way it was written, all that was fantastic.

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:40.040
[Guest]: But also somehow at that time, in that place, it was somehow reflecting a world that I knew,

00:10:40.040 --> 00:10:48.480
[Guest]: which was unusual, you know, still at that time in fiction that I was reading, even in

00:10:48.480 --> 00:10:52.200
[Guest]: fiction written by Indians, it was unusual.

00:10:52.200 --> 00:10:54.440
[Guest]: So yeah, I mean.

00:10:54.440 --> 00:10:58.560
[Amit Varma]: And that's very interesting because I can understand why you are a fan of Roald Dahl

00:10:58.560 --> 00:11:03.120
[Amit Varma]: and because, you know, like him again, you've written for both adults and children.

00:11:03.120 --> 00:11:06.800
[Amit Varma]: The Arundhati Roy took me a little by surprise because your voice is very different in a

00:11:06.800 --> 00:11:12.120
[Amit Varma]: good way in the sense that, I mean, I'm not a, my personal bias is that I'm not a fan

00:11:12.120 --> 00:11:17.640
[Amit Varma]: of the very highly stylized kind of writers for whom language is very important.

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:22.760
[Amit Varma]: And I find people like Rushdie and Arundhati a little excessive in that sense that your

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:25.960
[Amit Varma]: attention is constantly drawn to the writing style.

00:11:25.960 --> 00:11:30.960
[Amit Varma]: And I find that your style is, say, much more in a way of, say, Vikram said, very understated

00:11:30.960 --> 00:11:32.920
[Amit Varma]: and very clear.

00:11:32.920 --> 00:11:36.880
[Amit Varma]: And did you, you know, in your process of sort of writing, and especially when you were

00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:42.120
[Amit Varma]: writing your children's books, did you find yourself giving a lot of thought to, say,

00:11:42.120 --> 00:11:43.760
[Amit Varma]: the craft of writing?

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:44.760
[Amit Varma]: How do you write sentences?

00:11:44.760 --> 00:11:47.520
[Amit Varma]: How do you put together narratives?

00:11:47.520 --> 00:11:48.520
[Amit Varma]: What should you do?

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:49.520
[Guest]: What should you not do?

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:54.080
[Guest]: Yeah, I think, you know, with every book, it's been something that, you know, some,

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:59.320
[Guest]: something that I've had to learn in order to do it.

00:11:59.320 --> 00:12:05.680
[Guest]: And I think, you know, my first book was a collection of short stories.

00:12:05.680 --> 00:12:13.800
[Guest]: And I think there, a lot of the focus was on the craft of writing, I suggest, the sentence

00:12:13.800 --> 00:12:18.160
[Guest]: level stuff, you know, and that, which I enjoyed.

00:12:18.160 --> 00:12:21.120
[Guest]: And for me, it was the least taxing.

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:26.600
[Guest]: And for me, I find as a writer, the most difficult thing is plotting, and which is the sort of

00:12:26.600 --> 00:12:31.000
[Guest]: barrier I encountered when I, you know, after that, I wanted to, you know, I wanted to write

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:32.520
[Guest]: a novel.

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:39.920
[Guest]: And you can't, I mean, doing sort of meandering, plotless short stories is one thing.

00:12:39.920 --> 00:12:42.160
[Guest]: But plotless novel is a whole other thing.

00:12:42.160 --> 00:12:43.160
[Guest]: And of course, you can do that.

00:12:43.160 --> 00:12:45.600
[Guest]: But plotless novels are not even novels that I enjoy reading.

00:12:45.600 --> 00:12:48.520
[Guest]: I mean, I like plots, I like a story.

00:12:48.520 --> 00:12:54.680
[Guest]: I like, and I realized that it's to me, I think, four years and about six revisions

00:12:54.680 --> 00:13:00.080
[Guest]: to get that very slim novella done.

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:05.200
[Guest]: Because I was, in the end, I realized what the problem was not just that the plot was

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:07.480
[Guest]: not falling into place.

00:13:07.480 --> 00:13:12.440
[Guest]: But also, there was no momentum building and two things have to go together.

00:13:12.440 --> 00:13:17.280
[Guest]: You know, you have to have a kind of momentum build up to take the plot from one thing to

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:19.720
[Guest]: the next.

00:13:19.720 --> 00:13:22.480
[Guest]: So that was a difficult sort of experience.

00:13:22.480 --> 00:13:27.840
[Guest]: And I think the similar thing I learned with that, after that, I did this book for children,

00:13:27.840 --> 00:13:30.160
[Guest]: the story of Babur.

00:13:30.160 --> 00:13:32.440
[Guest]: And there, I learned the same thing.

00:13:32.440 --> 00:13:36.840
[Guest]: But even more, you know, because with kids, there was very little room for anything that

00:13:36.840 --> 00:13:42.040
[Guest]: is not moving the action forward, you know, something has to be happening.

00:13:42.040 --> 00:13:48.400
[Guest]: And I found that that was very energizing for me to have to do that, you know, as as

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:52.840
[Guest]: a writer, that was great fun of it that you know, that there was no there was no diversions,

00:13:52.840 --> 00:13:57.000
[Guest]: there were no digressions, you're just going from one thing to the next.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:01.320
[Guest]: And you know, maintain that, maintain interest and action.

00:14:01.320 --> 00:14:04.560
[Amit Varma]: Do you feel that changed you as a writer in general, writing for children?

00:14:04.560 --> 00:14:06.080
[Guest]: I think so.

00:14:06.080 --> 00:14:07.080
[Guest]: I do.

00:14:07.080 --> 00:14:09.880
[Guest]: I felt I felt a kind of livelier spirit.

00:14:09.880 --> 00:14:12.240
[Guest]: I don't know if that's how that sounds.

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:15.440
[Guest]: But yeah, I felt a greater energy.

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:17.760
[Guest]: And I went from there, I was working on another novel.

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:23.800
[Guest]: And I wrote that novel with something of that, you know, children's book, momentum and energy

00:14:23.800 --> 00:14:24.800
[Guest]: in mind.

00:14:24.800 --> 00:14:25.800
[Guest]: And it did.

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:27.280
[Guest]: It helped really did.

00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:29.160
[Amit Varma]: It was a...

00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:34.280
[Amit Varma]: And so your first brush with writing history would therefore have been the book on Babur.

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:37.680
[Amit Varma]: And like, of course, you had a readymade plot there.

00:14:37.680 --> 00:14:42.240
[Amit Varma]: But did the process of writing that book sort of change the way you look at the Mughals

00:14:42.240 --> 00:14:45.520
[Amit Varma]: or the way you looked at the history of that period?

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:57.080
[Guest]: I don't know if it changed it because I hadn't even thought, you know, that much about history

00:14:57.080 --> 00:15:01.800
[Guest]: in general or the Mughals in particular, except in the way that you know, everyone sort of

00:15:01.800 --> 00:15:04.800
[Guest]: when you come across something or you know.

00:15:04.800 --> 00:15:10.720
[Guest]: But I hadn't really taken any particular trouble to find out anything.

00:15:10.720 --> 00:15:14.040
[Guest]: And but it did.

00:15:14.040 --> 00:15:16.800
[Guest]: It took me completely by surprise.

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:22.280
[Guest]: What took me completely by surprise was the Babur Nama, which, you know, I started reading

00:15:22.280 --> 00:15:28.400
[Guest]: not really knowing what to expect and not...

00:15:28.400 --> 00:15:35.160
[Guest]: And then actually expecting more some kind of sort of dry recital of events or, you know,

00:15:35.160 --> 00:15:41.080
[Guest]: or sort of dates and facts and figures and things like that.

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:50.480
[Guest]: And instead, it turned out to be this really, really sort of lucid, unselfconscious account

00:15:50.480 --> 00:15:53.200
[Guest]: of this man's life.

00:15:53.200 --> 00:15:58.400
[Guest]: And it and you know, right in the beginning, like within the first few pages, there's a

00:15:58.400 --> 00:16:00.200
[Guest]: description, a barber is talking about his father.

00:16:00.200 --> 00:16:01.200
[Amit Varma]: Over eating.

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:02.200
[Amit Varma]: Over eating.

00:16:02.200 --> 00:16:04.320
[Guest]: He was sort of a rotund man.

00:16:04.320 --> 00:16:09.240
[Guest]: And once he had eaten and feasted, he would he was also sort of cheerful, he would laugh.

00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:14.600
[Guest]: And he says the laces of his tunic would snap open.

00:16:14.600 --> 00:16:21.400
[Guest]: And you know, immediately like the image you get is of this young child watching his father,

00:16:21.400 --> 00:16:25.320
[Guest]: the king, you know, his laces of his tunic snapping open.

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:29.400
[Guest]: And there's a sort of little mischief and humour and affection.

00:16:29.400 --> 00:16:32.400
[Amit Varma]: And such a literary detail also.

00:16:32.400 --> 00:16:33.400
[Guest]: Yes, that's also.

00:16:33.400 --> 00:16:34.400
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:16:34.400 --> 00:16:39.800
[Guest]: So, you know, that kind of detail that I wasn't expecting at all, but it really helped to

00:16:39.800 --> 00:16:44.920
[Guest]: get a sense of Babur the man.

00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:49.680
[Amit Varma]: And yet the Babur Nama is very different from, for example, the Jahangir Nama, in the sense

00:16:49.680 --> 00:16:54.520
[Amit Varma]: that you mentioned how the Jahangir Nama is really Jahangir was keeping a diary.

00:16:54.520 --> 00:16:56.840
[Unknown]: So it's not like a narrative written after a period of time.

00:16:56.840 --> 00:16:58.960
[Amit Varma]: It's life unfolding as it is.

00:16:58.960 --> 00:17:04.680
[Amit Varma]: And it has that immediacy and the seeming candour and the Babur Nama, Babur, you've

00:17:04.680 --> 00:17:08.520
[Amit Varma]: mentioned that he was sort of writing it with an eye on history as well.

00:17:08.520 --> 00:17:13.560
[Amit Varma]: It's also an act of, you know, creating a narrative about himself.

00:17:13.560 --> 00:17:16.800
[Guest]: He is sort of writing it as his memoirs.

00:17:16.800 --> 00:17:19.160
[Guest]: And Jahangir is writing it as his diary.

00:17:19.160 --> 00:17:22.640
[Guest]: So there is in that sense, just the texture of it is different.

00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:29.680
[Guest]: You know, Babur Nama is more like a record of significant things that happened in his

00:17:29.680 --> 00:17:30.680
[Guest]: life.

00:17:30.680 --> 00:17:35.200
[Guest]: But Jahangir is like exciting things happened yesterday.

00:17:35.200 --> 00:17:37.200
[Amit Varma]: You know that.

00:17:37.200 --> 00:17:42.360
[Unknown]: I saw a snake eating a rabbit.

00:17:42.360 --> 00:17:44.680
[Amit Varma]: And let's kind of come to Jahangir.

00:17:44.680 --> 00:17:49.080
[Amit Varma]: And it's very interesting that you chose Jahangir as a subject, because typically when you think

00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:52.760
[Amit Varma]: of the Mughals, of course, there were sort of six great Mughals before the decline began,

00:17:52.760 --> 00:17:58.320
[Amit Varma]: which is Babur Humayun, Akbar Jahangir, Shah Jahan and the infamous Aurangzeb.

00:17:58.320 --> 00:18:04.240
[Amit Varma]: And Jahangir is sort of like a lost figure who for a long time has not been taken seriously

00:18:04.240 --> 00:18:06.080
[Amit Varma]: by historians so much.

00:18:06.080 --> 00:18:10.320
[Amit Varma]: He's, you know, he's been painted as ineffectual.

00:18:10.320 --> 00:18:14.120
[Amit Varma]: He's not focused on conquering new territory like emperors are.

00:18:14.120 --> 00:18:16.120
[Amit Varma]: He's sort of a weak man.

00:18:16.120 --> 00:18:17.840
[Amit Varma]: He drinks a lot and so on.

00:18:17.840 --> 00:18:23.040
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that I learned while reading your book was that historians are

00:18:23.040 --> 00:18:27.960
[Amit Varma]: now beginning to feel that he wasn't necessarily like this, that these are the imperatives

00:18:27.960 --> 00:18:35.800
[Amit Varma]: that come from one how Shah Jahan wanted to portray him to sort of justify his own acts

00:18:35.800 --> 00:18:43.520
[Amit Varma]: and to the work of Thomas Rowe, the East India Company emissary who was at the time there.

00:18:43.520 --> 00:18:49.080
[Amit Varma]: And he also had his own incentives, if I may use a term I use often on the show, in painting

00:18:49.080 --> 00:18:50.560
[Amit Varma]: Jahangir in a particular way.

00:18:50.560 --> 00:18:52.200
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about this.

00:18:52.200 --> 00:18:57.520
[Guest]: Yeah, no, so that was that was interesting for me also to discover this.

00:18:57.520 --> 00:19:03.680
[Guest]: This particular argument is made by Corinne Lefebvre, who's a French historian who is

00:19:03.680 --> 00:19:08.160
[Guest]: sort of re-evaluating both Jahangir's life and the Jahangir Nama.

00:19:08.160 --> 00:19:15.960
[Guest]: And so when I was writing this book, in the first draft of it, the idea that I had of

00:19:15.960 --> 00:19:27.840
[Guest]: this man was of like a sort of well-meaning, amiable, but dissolute, overall, not sort

00:19:27.840 --> 00:19:32.840
[Guest]: of a lightweight, you know, entertaining, but not for the ages.

00:19:32.840 --> 00:19:39.160
[Guest]: I mean, on the other hand, he ruled for 22 years, but even that, the generally accepted

00:19:39.160 --> 00:19:46.240
[Guest]: sense that you gather if you read, you know, around him, is that Akbar had built up such

00:19:46.240 --> 00:19:52.840
[Guest]: a strong empire that you would need, you know, another Akbar to even to undo it.

00:19:52.840 --> 00:19:59.720
[Guest]: You know, even that would require more sort of energy than Jahangir was inclined to display

00:19:59.720 --> 00:20:00.720
[Guest]: in his life.

00:20:00.720 --> 00:20:06.400
[Guest]: But, you know, I was discussing this with a friend who's also a historian who was a

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:10.560
[Guest]: great help to me in the writing of this book, Anubhuti Maurya.

00:20:10.560 --> 00:20:17.160
[Guest]: Well, you know, but she said, it's not really necessarily true that just on the momentum

00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:22.280
[Guest]: of Akbar's centralization of power and creation of empire, that Jahangir would have been able

00:20:22.280 --> 00:20:24.720
[Guest]: to rule for 22 years.

00:20:24.720 --> 00:20:27.800
[Guest]: Because you know, dynasties can collapse at any time.

00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:36.920
[Guest]: I mean, even today you can have governments falling or, you know, countries changing overnight

00:20:36.920 --> 00:20:38.960
[Guest]: that can happen.

00:20:38.960 --> 00:20:43.360
[Guest]: So certainly, you know, it's worth thinking that, you know, he must be doing something

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:45.160
[Guest]: right.

00:20:45.160 --> 00:20:50.360
[Guest]: And then it was in fact Anubhuti who introduced me to the work of this Corian Lefebvre.

00:20:50.360 --> 00:20:54.640
[Guest]: And she's written this fantastic, in which he makes this argument that, you know, this

00:20:54.640 --> 00:21:02.000
[Guest]: idea that we have of Jahangir being the sort of weakling controlled by his wife and not

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:03.000
[Guest]: really up to much.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:08.800
[Guest]: Well, it comes from one, the fact that there is four contemporary accounts of his reign

00:21:08.800 --> 00:21:10.640
[Guest]: are limited only to him.

00:21:10.640 --> 00:21:16.560
[Guest]: There's only the Jahangir Nama because, you know, if the emperor is writing his own diary,

00:21:16.560 --> 00:21:19.840
[Guest]: then your history, who else will dare to?

00:21:19.840 --> 00:21:28.960
[Guest]: And then there is this propaganda that travels down almost 400 years unchanged via Shah Jahan,

00:21:28.960 --> 00:21:31.440
[Guest]: his historians who come after Jahangir.

00:21:31.440 --> 00:21:36.280
[Guest]: And Shah Jahan has rebelled against his father in the last years of his reign and they never

00:21:36.280 --> 00:21:37.880
[Guest]: quite make up.

00:21:37.880 --> 00:21:43.600
[Guest]: So once Shah Jahan ascends the throne, he has to justify his rebellion.

00:21:43.600 --> 00:21:49.840
[Guest]: And the only way he can, and he can't justify it by saying that, he can't say that, you

00:21:49.840 --> 00:21:54.080
[Guest]: know, there was something that Jahangir was a bad king, because that would then justify

00:21:54.080 --> 00:21:55.400
[Guest]: rebellions against him.

00:21:55.400 --> 00:21:57.560
[Guest]: You cannot rebel against the emperor.

00:21:57.560 --> 00:22:03.160
[Guest]: So he has to say that he was unable and unfit to be king because he was controlled by his

00:22:03.160 --> 00:22:04.920
[Guest]: wife, Noor Jahan.

00:22:04.920 --> 00:22:09.640
[Guest]: And Noor Jahan survives 20 years after Jahangir goes and Shah Jahan keeps a very close eye

00:22:09.640 --> 00:22:15.160
[Guest]: on her the entire time, keeps him virtually imprisoned in Lahore.

00:22:15.160 --> 00:22:20.520
[Guest]: She plays no public role whatsoever after that.

00:22:20.520 --> 00:22:24.760
[Guest]: And this idea, I mean, so much so is that there's a painting from Shah Jahan's reign

00:22:24.760 --> 00:22:31.840
[Guest]: which has Akbar sitting in the middle and there's Shah Jahan to his left and Jahangir

00:22:31.840 --> 00:22:33.120
[Guest]: to his right.

00:22:33.120 --> 00:22:37.880
[Guest]: And you know, Akbar is sort of blithely handing the crown over to Shah Jahan while Jahangir

00:22:37.880 --> 00:22:44.280
[Amit Varma]: is sort of looking on, looking very sullen and a little sad.

00:22:44.280 --> 00:22:48.880
[Amit Varma]: And this was part of the sort of, so these painters and Shah Jahan's times who were making

00:22:48.880 --> 00:22:51.880
[Amit Varma]: all these paintings are kind of like the IT cell of today, right?

00:22:51.880 --> 00:22:57.560
[Amit Varma]: His IT cell, which is pushing out these false narratives, I guess.

00:22:57.560 --> 00:23:01.240
[Amit Varma]: And I guess another major work of that period, which everyone refers to is, of course, Abu

00:23:01.240 --> 00:23:06.320
[Amit Varma]: Fazal's, you know, histories of Akbar, which are fairly hagiographic and he's just in awe

00:23:06.320 --> 00:23:08.880
[Amit Varma]: of Akbar and he also doesn't like Jahangir very much.

00:23:08.880 --> 00:23:10.880
[Amit Varma]: So Jahangir doesn't come across as very well.

00:23:10.880 --> 00:23:16.560
[Amit Varma]: And then Jahangir, of course, gives him the ultimate bad book review by getting him beheaded

00:23:16.560 --> 00:23:22.480
[Amit Varma]: and throwing his head into a latrine in one of the colorful details you've sort of described

00:23:22.480 --> 00:23:23.480
[Amit Varma]: in your book.

00:23:23.480 --> 00:23:27.920
[Amit Varma]: You've also spoken in the past about how the way you looked at Jahangir Nama, the book

00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:31.960
[Amit Varma]: changed over time, that at first you just looked at it as an honest diary, that every

00:23:31.960 --> 00:23:33.480
[Amit Varma]: day the guy is writing a diary.

00:23:33.480 --> 00:23:36.440
[Amit Varma]: But then you realize there was probably a little more to it than that.

00:23:36.440 --> 00:23:37.880
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about that.

00:23:37.880 --> 00:23:38.880
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:23:38.880 --> 00:23:46.760
[Guest]: So again, for this again, I mean, let it to Corinne Lefevre, who describes it as, as in

00:23:46.760 --> 00:23:51.160
[Guest]: an essay, she calls it a model of imperial propaganda.

00:23:51.160 --> 00:23:56.440
[Guest]: And I, you know, because when you the first time you read it, I recommend it to everyone

00:23:56.440 --> 00:23:59.600
[Guest]: now having read it, it's really very readable.

00:23:59.600 --> 00:24:00.600
[Guest]: It's entertaining.

00:24:00.600 --> 00:24:01.600
[Guest]: It's fluent.

00:24:01.600 --> 00:24:02.600
[Guest]: It's lucid.

00:24:02.600 --> 00:24:03.600
[Guest]: It's well written.

00:24:03.600 --> 00:24:10.160
[Guest]: It's got, it's got all kinds of emotions and, you know, action and adventure of all sorts.

00:24:10.160 --> 00:24:16.480
[Guest]: So so and Jahangir is a good writer and you know, like good writers, he can make you believe

00:24:16.480 --> 00:24:18.160
[Guest]: him as the narrator.

00:24:18.160 --> 00:24:23.960
[Guest]: You know, he makes you sympathetic to him and he makes you be on his side.

00:24:23.960 --> 00:24:30.240
[Guest]: But it doesn't mean that he was not aware that this was a public document.

00:24:30.240 --> 00:24:37.280
[Guest]: And in fact, at some point, maybe about some midway through his reign, he has copies of

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:44.560
[Guest]: the of the Jahangir Nama that as it exists then made and distributed to kings around

00:24:44.560 --> 00:24:46.680
[Guest]: the you know, in the in the region.

00:24:46.680 --> 00:24:51.440
[Guest]: And he says, I sent it out and I meant it this Jahangir Nama to be a model of how to

00:24:51.440 --> 00:24:52.440
[Guest]: rule.

00:24:52.440 --> 00:24:58.560
[Guest]: So he's actually thinking of it in those terms.

00:24:58.560 --> 00:25:05.360
[Amit Varma]: And but all the human frailties that kind of come across like his drinking, for example,

00:25:05.360 --> 00:25:11.160
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, I mean, is that sort of slipping through the cracks of his, you know, posturing

00:25:11.160 --> 00:25:12.160
[Amit Varma]: as such?

00:25:12.160 --> 00:25:19.400
[Amit Varma]: Or does he feel that, you know, I mean, how convinced are you of this view of, you know,

00:25:19.400 --> 00:25:21.920
[Amit Varma]: having read both translations of the book?

00:25:21.920 --> 00:25:22.920
[Guest]: How convinced?

00:25:22.920 --> 00:25:26.880
[Guest]: I, you know, I would say that, let's say the drinking, right?

00:25:26.880 --> 00:25:32.960
[Guest]: He's talking, he's talking about the drinking, he's very seemingly, very strangely frank

00:25:32.960 --> 00:25:33.960
[Guest]: about it.

00:25:33.960 --> 00:25:36.440
[Guest]: You know, he says that I started drinking at 18.

00:25:36.440 --> 00:25:39.960
[Guest]: He tells the story in great detail, says I started drinking at 18.

00:25:39.960 --> 00:25:41.560
[Guest]: And I was out on a hunt.

00:25:41.560 --> 00:25:48.160
[Guest]: And, you know, somebody got him just a little sort of pint or half a pint of sweet wine.

00:25:48.160 --> 00:25:49.440
[Guest]: And he enjoyed it.

00:25:49.440 --> 00:25:55.640
[Guest]: And before you know it, he's drinking 20 goblets of double distilled liquor a day, 14 during

00:25:55.640 --> 00:25:57.880
[Amit Varma]: the day and the remainder at night.

00:25:57.880 --> 00:26:01.960
[Amit Varma]: And then he goes on to elaborate that that's equivalent to six Hindustani seers, which

00:26:01.960 --> 00:26:04.600
[Amit Varma]: is equivalent to one and a half Iranian morns.

00:26:04.600 --> 00:26:06.760
[Guest]: And he's a scientific man of measurement.

00:26:06.760 --> 00:26:10.120
[Guest]: Yeah, he likes, he likes to be clear.

00:26:10.120 --> 00:26:14.800
[Guest]: And then he says that I was drinking so much that in my hangovers, my hands used to shake

00:26:14.800 --> 00:26:17.680
[Guest]: so much that I couldn't even hold the goblet.

00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:20.680
[Guest]: Somebody else would have to pour the liquor down my throat.

00:26:20.680 --> 00:26:24.440
[Guest]: And he says, I called the doctor and the doctor said to me that if you don't stop, you'll

00:26:24.440 --> 00:26:27.160
[Guest]: be dead in in six months.

00:26:27.160 --> 00:26:31.000
[Guest]: And then he goes through his entire sort of de-addiction program.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:33.120
[Amit Varma]: That was also done very meticulously.

00:26:33.120 --> 00:26:37.240
[Guest]: He reduces it bit by bit, takes it down to six.

00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:42.800
[Guest]: And mixes his spirit with wine, like dilutes the spirit with wine in order to...

00:26:42.800 --> 00:26:48.120
[Amit Varma]: So that's how you give up drinking, gentlemen, dilute your spirits with wine.

00:26:48.120 --> 00:26:52.400
[Guest]: And have a little opium during the day to get you through.

00:26:52.400 --> 00:26:58.720
[Guest]: So on the one hand, you know, there's, it seems as if like, oh, OK, if you look at it

00:26:58.720 --> 00:27:05.200
[Guest]: from a sort of a modern 21st century perspective, it would appear like, oh, this is like a,

00:27:05.200 --> 00:27:06.880
[Guest]: you know, sort of a confessional narrative.

00:27:06.880 --> 00:27:14.280
[Guest]: You know, how I almost died from drink, but then rose to be emperor.

00:27:14.280 --> 00:27:18.160
[Guest]: And again, because I'm not a historian, I don't want to say like too, I don't want to

00:27:18.160 --> 00:27:19.160
[Guest]: say things with too much authority.

00:27:19.160 --> 00:27:23.760
[Guest]: But it's also like, you know, we're talking about the 17th century, drinking is not perhaps,

00:27:23.760 --> 00:27:31.240
[Guest]: or at least addiction to drink is not viewed in the same way as it would be now.

00:27:31.240 --> 00:27:34.480
[Guest]: You know, there are there are problems with drinking then.

00:27:34.480 --> 00:27:38.880
[Guest]: I mean, there are there are sort of religious problems with it.

00:27:38.880 --> 00:27:44.600
[Guest]: But the problem of addiction doesn't exist, perhaps, in the way that, you know, that it

00:27:44.600 --> 00:27:45.600
[Amit Varma]: might...

00:27:45.600 --> 00:27:47.600
[Amit Varma]: That we perceive it now, that there is a stigma on.

00:27:47.600 --> 00:27:53.240
[Guest]: Yeah, so perhaps, you know, when he's writing, he's not writing against, you know, against

00:27:53.240 --> 00:27:54.240
[Guest]: stigma.

00:27:54.240 --> 00:28:00.520
[Guest]: Or, you know, when he writes about ordering the execution of the assassination of Abul

00:28:00.520 --> 00:28:05.400
[Guest]: Fazal, which he again writes with very frank and forthright way.

00:28:05.400 --> 00:28:09.880
[Guest]: He said this guy was forever making snide remarks about me to my father.

00:28:09.880 --> 00:28:11.360
[Guest]: So I knew I had to get rid of him.

00:28:11.360 --> 00:28:16.480
[Guest]: So I asked this Bir Singh Bundela if he would kindly waylay him.

00:28:16.480 --> 00:28:19.240
[Guest]: And he did and he sent me his head.

00:28:19.240 --> 00:28:24.360
[Guest]: And he says it as if, you know, it's a sort of cold blooded murder, really, that he's

00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:29.480
[Guest]: ordered of, you know, a man that he must have known for most of his life.

00:28:29.480 --> 00:28:35.160
[Guest]: And his father's like really one of his closest friends and advisors.

00:28:35.160 --> 00:28:42.800
[Guest]: So but again, you know, and I was again discussing this with Anupooti, and who said that, you

00:28:42.800 --> 00:28:49.240
[Guest]: know, again, this could be a, in a way, you know, is he saying here that, you know, this

00:28:49.240 --> 00:28:55.720
[Guest]: is, let's say in the 17th century, if you are aiming to be king, or you are an emperor,

00:28:55.720 --> 00:29:00.960
[Guest]: the image that you project of yourself is of a man who will not let anyone stand between

00:29:00.960 --> 00:29:06.680
[Guest]: him and the throne, a certain ruthlessness is necessary, you know, it has to have to

00:29:06.680 --> 00:29:07.680
[Amit Varma]: be that.

00:29:07.680 --> 00:29:09.240
[Amit Varma]: And it's almost normalized.

00:29:09.240 --> 00:29:14.200
[Amit Varma]: So it's not even something that it seems remarkable and, you know, and we'll come to other, I

00:29:14.200 --> 00:29:18.280
[Amit Varma]: want to ask you questions about a couple of things you raised like drinking and addiction,

00:29:18.280 --> 00:29:24.400
[Amit Varma]: number one, and number two, about the sort of casual cruelty that can sometimes happen.

00:29:24.400 --> 00:29:26.720
[Amit Varma]: But you know, let's kind of go back to the narrative.

00:29:26.720 --> 00:29:30.560
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you start your book essentially with Akbar.

00:29:30.560 --> 00:29:36.480
[Amit Varma]: And a significant part of the story of Jahangir is really the story of Akbar wanting a son.

00:29:36.480 --> 00:29:42.440
[Amit Varma]: And just to, you know, set some context, we often think of, you know, when we, we look

00:29:42.440 --> 00:29:46.640
[Amit Varma]: at history in a sense with the hindsight bias, it's happened, we take it for granted.

00:29:46.640 --> 00:29:51.300
[Amit Varma]: We take it for granted that the Mughal Empire was this great empire that lasted centuries.

00:29:51.300 --> 00:29:56.640
[Amit Varma]: But as you've pointed out, and as Ramakoti spoke about in her episode with me a few weeks

00:29:56.640 --> 00:30:01.040
[Amit Varma]: earlier, it wasn't such a done deal, you know, so Babur came over, you know, he was, well,

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:06.080
[Amit Varma]: when he ascended to his throne, he came over, he conquered a bit of it, but then they lost

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:08.840
[Amit Varma]: it and Humayun was in exile for 15 years.

00:30:08.840 --> 00:30:14.080
[Amit Varma]: He was in fact in exile when he fell in love with Hamida Banu Begum in Afghanistan, I think,

00:30:14.080 --> 00:30:16.680
[Amit Varma]: and he asked for her hand and she was like, who are you?

00:30:16.680 --> 00:30:20.560
[Amit Varma]: You're, you know, you're running right now, you're not a king.

00:30:20.560 --> 00:30:24.520
[Amit Varma]: And anyway, so that kind of worked out and Humayun comes back and he's just taken over

00:30:24.520 --> 00:30:26.360
[Amit Varma]: the kingdom and then he dies.

00:30:26.360 --> 00:30:28.880
[Amit Varma]: And Akbar ascends at 14.

00:30:28.880 --> 00:30:35.280
[Amit Varma]: And the empire that he leaves, that Jahangir is born into, is just an awesome, incredible

00:30:35.280 --> 00:30:36.880
[Amit Varma]: empire.

00:30:36.880 --> 00:30:38.840
[Amit Varma]: And Jahangir is a first son.

00:30:38.840 --> 00:30:42.600
[Amit Varma]: There is no dynasty without at least one son coming along.

00:30:42.600 --> 00:30:49.280
[Amit Varma]: So you've written in your book about how badly Jahangir desires a son and when he is born,

00:30:49.280 --> 00:30:54.040
[Amit Varma]: you write, quote, there is only so much self-control a joyful father can have.

00:30:54.040 --> 00:30:57.760
[Amit Varma]: Celebrations burst upon Agra like lightning upon a rain-ripe sky.

00:30:57.760 --> 00:31:00.520
[Amit Varma]: Heaps and heaps of gold were scattered, says one writer.

00:31:00.520 --> 00:31:03.520
[Amit Varma]: Prisoners and dungeons across the empire were set free.

00:31:03.520 --> 00:31:07.520
[Amit Varma]: For days, poets composed odes to the prince, stop quote.

00:31:07.520 --> 00:31:13.280
[Amit Varma]: And then you quote Abu Fazl, Akbar's infamous biographer, quote, the auspicious birth of

00:31:13.280 --> 00:31:17.760
[Amit Varma]: the world illuminating pearl of the mansion of dominion and fortune, the night gleaming

00:31:17.760 --> 00:31:24.800
[Amit Varma]: jewel of the casket of greatness and glory, namely of Prince Sultan Salim, stop quote.

00:31:24.800 --> 00:31:29.040
[Amit Varma]: So Akbar wanted the son so badly and he loves his son so much.

00:31:29.040 --> 00:31:35.400
[Amit Varma]: And yet there is such a sort of tension here because a son inevitably, no matter what he

00:31:35.400 --> 00:31:37.320
[Amit Varma]: is, will be a disappointment to his father.

00:31:37.320 --> 00:31:41.200
[Guest]: I mean, not any son and any father, but you know, this was Akbar.

00:31:41.200 --> 00:31:42.200
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:31:42.200 --> 00:31:44.720
[Guest]: So Akbar really, I mean, who could have not disappointed him?

00:31:44.720 --> 00:31:50.320
[Guest]: It's not, you know, I wouldn't want to be, I wouldn't have wanted to be in Salim's place.

00:31:50.320 --> 00:31:54.760
[Guest]: It was because this guy, like Akbar really is extraordinary.

00:31:54.760 --> 00:32:00.520
[Guest]: You know, he is, I mean, there is a reason why he shines brighter than other people in

00:32:00.520 --> 00:32:01.520
[Guest]: history.

00:32:01.520 --> 00:32:07.440
[Guest]: And there are some people like that who really accomplished far more in one lifetime than

00:32:07.440 --> 00:32:09.880
[Guest]: most people could in 10.

00:32:09.880 --> 00:32:15.760
[Guest]: And there's no, I mean, when he becomes whatever, I mean, emperor, but emperor of what?

00:32:15.760 --> 00:32:19.280
[Guest]: You know, basically of Delhi, he's not even in Delhi, he's still in Punjab.

00:32:19.280 --> 00:32:27.480
[Guest]: He's there still he and Beram Khan is still in pursuit of Sikandar Sur and Mayun slips

00:32:27.480 --> 00:32:33.200
[Guest]: and falls and breaks his head and Akbar is suddenly king, but there's no reason for him

00:32:33.200 --> 00:32:34.200
[Guest]: to remain.

00:32:34.200 --> 00:32:40.520
[Guest]: There's loads of competition, and not least from him, who is one of the, you know, great

00:32:40.520 --> 00:32:48.080
[Guest]: generals of that time and has fought several battles and never lost one and is far more

00:32:48.080 --> 00:32:56.880
[Guest]: experienced and has a big, huge army and lots of elephants and he's primed to take over,

00:32:56.880 --> 00:33:00.360
[Guest]: you know, and they face each other in Panipat.

00:33:00.360 --> 00:33:06.000
[Guest]: And there, I mean, the battle from, you know, whatever I've read of it, it sort of, it was

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:07.360
[Guest]: a fairly equal battle.

00:33:07.360 --> 00:33:14.120
[Guest]: And then he does have a stroke of luck because Hemu is struck in the eye with an arrow and

00:33:14.120 --> 00:33:16.280
[Guest]: he and he falls.

00:33:16.280 --> 00:33:21.760
[Guest]: And the logic of battles at the time was if the leader collapses, or the commander collapses,

00:33:21.760 --> 00:33:26.800
[Guest]: the army collapses, you know, which is really very inefficient, but that's how it was.

00:33:26.800 --> 00:33:32.600
[Guest]: So he, you know, so Hemu collapsed and so did the rest of his army.

00:33:32.600 --> 00:33:37.920
[Guest]: And so then, you know, that battle is won, you know, partly by luck.

00:33:37.920 --> 00:33:43.000
[Guest]: But after that, it's not I mean, luck doesn't get him through, you know, the next 50 odd

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:51.240
[Guest]: years that he lives and goes from strength to strength to strength, sorting down rebellion

00:33:51.240 --> 00:33:52.560
[Guest]: after rebellion after rebellion.

00:33:52.560 --> 00:33:56.720
[Guest]: And so many people are vying for power.

00:33:56.720 --> 00:34:01.560
[Guest]: And you know, not only is he doing that, not only is he increasing his physical geography

00:34:01.560 --> 00:34:07.000
[Guest]: of his realm, just sort of going from one conquest to another, he's also changing its

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:08.000
[Guest]: systems.

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:12.800
[Guest]: So he's back from, you know, conquering Gujarat and he sits down, he says, now let's rethink

00:34:12.800 --> 00:34:17.560
[Guest]: our revenue model or our, you know, administration or how we organize the Mansabdars.

00:34:17.560 --> 00:34:19.400
[Guest]: He's very interested in all of that.

00:34:19.400 --> 00:34:23.800
[Guest]: Then he's also doing this, you know, he's got these great translation projects, he's

00:34:23.800 --> 00:34:27.640
[Guest]: got building projects, he's got music and all of that.

00:34:27.640 --> 00:34:32.120
[Guest]: I mean, you know, so all of this is going on at the same time.

00:34:32.120 --> 00:34:37.480
[Guest]: This is a man who, I mean, reading about him, you feel a little exhausted.

00:34:37.480 --> 00:34:39.680
[Guest]: You know, he just never stops.

00:34:39.680 --> 00:34:46.000
[Amit Varma]: It must be like literally a one in a millennium chance that all of these qualities converge

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:47.480
[Amit Varma]: upon one person.

00:34:47.480 --> 00:34:50.760
[Amit Varma]: He fits the role of the great conqueror.

00:34:50.760 --> 00:34:57.080
[Amit Varma]: He's also a great public policy man to use modern terminology where he's reforming his

00:34:57.080 --> 00:35:00.920
[Amit Varma]: tax revenue systems and his systems of governance and all of that.

00:35:00.920 --> 00:35:05.240
[Amit Varma]: At the same time, he's a great patron of the arts, partly with the help of all these painters

00:35:05.240 --> 00:35:10.400
[Amit Varma]: whom Arjun brought back from Persia famously and which tradition, which is Sanjay Hangeer,

00:35:10.400 --> 00:35:14.040
[Amit Varma]: of course, continues to great with great success.

00:35:14.040 --> 00:35:16.480
[Amit Varma]: And also he is a serious intellectual.

00:35:16.480 --> 00:35:20.840
[Amit Varma]: He's thinking about religion, all of these different ideas, trying to weave these strands

00:35:20.840 --> 00:35:21.880
[Amit Varma]: together.

00:35:21.880 --> 00:35:27.280
[Amit Varma]: And he finally has a son and the son sits around drinking all day and examining animals

00:35:27.280 --> 00:35:33.160
[Amit Varma]: and shows no interest in conquest, keeps making excuses to kind of, I mean, one of the themes

00:35:33.160 --> 00:35:37.840
[Amit Varma]: that ran through your book is that your book is full of basically a father sending a son

00:35:37.840 --> 00:35:39.440
[Amit Varma]: to conquer something or the other.

00:35:39.440 --> 00:35:43.440
[Amit Varma]: Quite often the decan and the son is making excuses and he's going here and he's going

00:35:43.440 --> 00:35:48.120
[Amit Varma]: there and you know, Akbar sends all his kids to do this and they all kind of make a mess

00:35:48.120 --> 00:35:49.320
[Amit Varma]: of it.

00:35:49.320 --> 00:35:56.600
[Amit Varma]: And Jahangir then sends, you know, eventually Khurram has a semi success of sorts.

00:35:56.600 --> 00:36:02.320
[Amit Varma]: And I was kind of interested by the, you know, again, just to talk a little bit about drinking

00:36:02.320 --> 00:36:07.400
[Amit Varma]: and addiction, because as we were, you know, chatting while coming here, I was sort of

00:36:07.400 --> 00:36:09.600
[Amit Varma]: a professional poker player for five years.

00:36:09.600 --> 00:36:16.600
[Amit Varma]: I've seen people addicted to gambling, I've written columns about addiction and it kind

00:36:16.600 --> 00:36:21.720
[Amit Varma]: of and I'm again just thinking aloud and tell me what your response is that I think a lot

00:36:21.720 --> 00:36:26.960
[Amit Varma]: of people have addictive personalities, but what they're addicted to is not specifically

00:36:26.960 --> 00:36:32.320
[Amit Varma]: thing A or thing B or activity C, it's dopamine to the brain.

00:36:32.320 --> 00:36:35.040
[Amit Varma]: And the question is, where do you get that dopamine from?

00:36:35.040 --> 00:36:38.800
[Amit Varma]: And in modern times, it could be safe from gambling, you push chips forward, you get

00:36:38.800 --> 00:36:42.960
[Amit Varma]: dopamine rush to your head, it could be from playing online chess, which I think I might

00:36:42.960 --> 00:36:48.360
[Amit Varma]: have been addicted to online chess, or it could come largely from social media as well.

00:36:48.360 --> 00:36:53.400
[Amit Varma]: In today's day and time, where you know, every notification gives you a hit every like gives

00:36:53.400 --> 00:36:55.020
[Amit Varma]: you a dopamine hit.

00:36:55.020 --> 00:36:59.920
[Amit Varma]: But in those times, like when I try to imagine how are people spending their time all day,

00:36:59.920 --> 00:37:04.200
[Amit Varma]: reading is not so common, there is no television, there are no movies, there is perhaps thankfully

00:37:04.200 --> 00:37:09.200
[Amit Varma]: no cricket or people would be impaled, umpires would be impaled upon cricket fields.

00:37:09.200 --> 00:37:11.960
[Amit Varma]: But there is a lot of wine and there's a lot of variety of wine.

00:37:11.960 --> 00:37:16.720
[Amit Varma]: So if people are going to get addicted, they will get addicted to that and all of Akbar's

00:37:16.720 --> 00:37:21.040
[Amit Varma]: children get addicted to it, you know, Murad and Dhani are the other two kids, they kind

00:37:21.040 --> 00:37:27.040
[Amit Varma]: of so you know, what sort of your response to that and also just thinking about taking

00:37:27.040 --> 00:37:28.560
[Amit Varma]: off from that?

00:37:28.560 --> 00:37:35.000
[Amit Varma]: What's a typical day like in the life of, let's say somebody living under Akbar or under

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:36.720
[Amit Varma]: Jahangir?

00:37:36.720 --> 00:37:37.720
[Amit Varma]: You know, what are they doing?

00:37:37.720 --> 00:37:39.400
[Amit Varma]: How are they spending their time?

00:37:39.400 --> 00:37:40.400
[Amit Varma]: How do they?

00:37:40.400 --> 00:37:44.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I know it's a very nice question, which historians can scoff at me for asking.

00:37:44.960 --> 00:37:52.760
[Guest]: Well, to the first part, we're sure, yeah, I mean, wine was plentifully obviously available.

00:37:52.760 --> 00:37:58.000
[Guest]: And it wasn't just, you know, Akbar's sons who were addicted, but you know, the nobility

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:03.520
[Guest]: generally and the sons of the nobility generally like even you know, Man Singh's son, I think

00:38:03.520 --> 00:38:09.040
[Guest]: he has, you know, four or five sons and of that, I think at least two or three die of

00:38:09.040 --> 00:38:10.040
[Guest]: drinking.

00:38:10.040 --> 00:38:16.520
[Guest]: And the Akbar Nama, Jahangir Nama, they're littered with the accounts of these sort of,

00:38:16.520 --> 00:38:22.080
[Guest]: in fact, littered with corpses of men who have perished from drink.

00:38:22.080 --> 00:38:25.680
[Guest]: But I suppose there was also, they have one or two alternatives.

00:38:25.680 --> 00:38:27.000
[Guest]: Hunting was one.

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:30.600
[Guest]: Certainly, Jahangir, you could almost say addicted to it.

00:38:30.600 --> 00:38:37.280
[Guest]: He does a census at one point asking, he wants to calculate how many animals he's killed

00:38:37.280 --> 00:38:42.640
[Guest]: between the age of 12 and about 50 or so that he is when he orders the census.

00:38:42.640 --> 00:38:48.640
[Guest]: And the amount comes to the rather obscene amount of 17,167 animals.

00:38:48.640 --> 00:38:53.120
[Amit Varma]: Out of which you mentioned 10,000 are pigeons.

00:38:53.120 --> 00:38:59.000
[Guest]: Yes, I was very pleased to learn this because it sort of, it makes me feel a little bit

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:00.000
[Guest]: better.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:04.520
[Guest]: And 86, I think, were lions.

00:39:04.520 --> 00:39:09.360
[Guest]: So there was at least one snake, as we know, if you count that.

00:39:09.360 --> 00:39:10.360
[Guest]: And one rabbit.

00:39:10.360 --> 00:39:11.360
[Guest]: And one rabbit.

00:39:11.360 --> 00:39:15.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it could be argued that the rabbit would have died anyway.

00:39:15.560 --> 00:39:17.560
[Guest]: Yeah, or maybe the rabbit escaped.

00:39:17.560 --> 00:39:18.560
[Amit Varma]: Or the rabbit fell out.

00:39:18.560 --> 00:39:19.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, the rabbit fell out of the...

00:39:19.560 --> 00:39:20.560
[Amit Varma]: The rabbit fell out.

00:39:20.560 --> 00:39:21.560
[Guest]: Maybe the rabbit just...

00:39:21.560 --> 00:39:30.160
[Amit Varma]: But a rabbit with severe post-traumatic stress disorder, if it's gone inside and outside.

00:39:30.160 --> 00:39:31.160
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:39:31.160 --> 00:39:35.880
[Guest]: And so, you know, definitely that and I think the other thing, I mean, the Mughals do exhibit

00:39:35.880 --> 00:39:42.560
[Guest]: a sense of tendency, not just towards addiction, but to kind of, you know, obsessive compulsive

00:39:42.560 --> 00:39:48.520
[Guest]: sort of OCD type of behavior when it comes to record keeping amongst other things.

00:39:48.520 --> 00:39:55.400
[Guest]: You know, they just, everything is noted down like in just ridiculous detail.

00:39:55.400 --> 00:40:02.920
[Guest]: You know how, not just the contents of the treasury, but, you know, the ranks of elephants,

00:40:02.920 --> 00:40:10.400
[Guest]: the ranks of mules, the, you know, the different sort of guns in the artillery, the, you know,

00:40:10.400 --> 00:40:15.120
[Guest]: I mean, every conceivable thing is noted down and filed.

00:40:15.120 --> 00:40:22.480
[Guest]: So, you know, and like this one of these Englishmen who travels there says that everything that

00:40:22.480 --> 00:40:29.560
[Guest]: happens during the day in the emperor's life is written down by writers, including what

00:40:29.560 --> 00:40:36.440
[Guest]: he eats, you know, and his sort of going to the necessity, all of that is meticulously

00:40:36.440 --> 00:40:37.440
[Guest]: recorded.

00:40:37.440 --> 00:40:42.680
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting, you seem to be indicating that this is not just a matter of, you know,

00:40:42.680 --> 00:40:45.880
[Amit Varma]: good efficient practice that you record everything, but there's something obsessive compulsive

00:40:45.880 --> 00:40:46.880
[Amit Varma]: about it.

00:40:46.880 --> 00:40:52.040
[Amit Varma]: So again, would go back to the thing of this also creates hits of dopamine in some way.

00:40:52.040 --> 00:40:56.840
[Guest]: It seems to me, because you're like, why would you want such minute details of, you know,

00:40:56.840 --> 00:40:57.840
[Guest]: recording?

00:40:57.840 --> 00:41:03.240
[Guest]: And then it's very, very professionally done, you know, that I think there are 14 recorders

00:41:03.240 --> 00:41:09.800
[Guest]: who work in shifts over the course of, you know, one week, two at a time, so that if

00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:12.040
[Guest]: one misses something out, the other one catches it.

00:41:12.040 --> 00:41:16.480
[Guest]: I mean, it's a professional meticulous enterprise.

00:41:16.480 --> 00:41:23.840
[Guest]: So that would be another way of sort of getting the dopamine hits.

00:41:23.840 --> 00:41:31.040
[Guest]: So but while you know, the daily life of the emperor was recorded in such minute detail,

00:41:31.040 --> 00:41:37.920
[Guest]: daily life of an ordinary person is more difficult to access.

00:41:37.920 --> 00:41:46.760
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, you get glimpses, you know, you get glimpses of, let's say in the in the

00:41:46.760 --> 00:41:53.560
[Guest]: court, when you know, you have descriptions of how the court is arranged and how people

00:41:53.560 --> 00:42:01.840
[Guest]: come and present their grievances or their demands or you know, what they what they want

00:42:01.840 --> 00:42:08.160
[Guest]: to get, you get you get glimpses of the kind of gossip and talk that might be circulating

00:42:08.160 --> 00:42:12.840
[Guest]: in the towns around the courts from some of these European writers.

00:42:12.840 --> 00:42:18.680
[Guest]: And I think I particularly liked what he said, Thomas Rowe is very shocked, because he says

00:42:18.680 --> 00:42:23.840
[Guest]: that, you know, whenever Jahangir makes a pronouncement, the minute he said it, it's,

00:42:23.840 --> 00:42:29.000
[Guest]: he says it's available for every rascal on the street to discuss and criticize.

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:34.280
[Guest]: And he says, you know, that Jahangir is really locked in the schedule that he has of his

00:42:34.280 --> 00:42:40.280
[Guest]: pre-dawn appearance and his, you know, the public darbar.

00:42:40.280 --> 00:42:47.880
[Guest]: And he says, just as the people are his slaves, so is he in a kind of reciprocal bondage with

00:42:47.880 --> 00:42:48.880
[Guest]: them.

00:42:48.880 --> 00:42:52.720
[Guest]: So he can't deviate from his routine very much.

00:42:52.720 --> 00:42:57.720
[Amit Varma]: And the daily situation is there's a pre-dawn sort of darbar, he comes out on the balcony

00:42:57.720 --> 00:43:00.760
[Amit Varma]: in the same much like Amitabh Bachchan today, I guess.

00:43:00.760 --> 00:43:04.200
[Amit Varma]: And then he takes a nap for two hours, and then he'll have his breakfast and all that

00:43:04.200 --> 00:43:07.120
[Amit Varma]: with whatever with opium morning hit of opium.

00:43:07.120 --> 00:43:11.080
[Amit Varma]: And then he has two darbars a day, you said one, you know, one before lunch, one after

00:43:11.080 --> 00:43:18.160
[Amit Varma]: lunch and it's it all sounds I mean, it would drive me to drink if I had to work so hard.

00:43:18.160 --> 00:43:26.000
[Amit Varma]: I was also, you know, struck by how, you know, like you point out at one time that one of

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:30.960
[Amit Varma]: the most common lines in Jahangir Nama is I summon the painters.

00:43:30.960 --> 00:43:36.880
[Amit Varma]: And it almost strikes me that he's almost like an Instagrammer, except a few centuries

00:43:36.880 --> 00:43:38.440
[Amit Varma]: before Instagram.

00:43:38.440 --> 00:43:41.000
[Amit Varma]: So he can't whip out a smartphone and capture something.

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:44.640
[Amit Varma]: So whenever he wants to capture something, he'll do it the royal way, send for his painters

00:43:44.640 --> 00:43:49.400
[Amit Varma]: and you know, a glacial pace Instagram.

00:43:49.400 --> 00:43:53.960
[Amit Varma]: And you point to how the only life painting of a dodo really came from his court, which

00:43:53.960 --> 00:43:58.320
[Amit Varma]: you reproduced in one of your talks, and it's a shockingly ugly bird.

00:43:58.320 --> 00:43:59.800
[Amit Varma]: What can one say of this?

00:43:59.800 --> 00:44:04.280
[Amit Varma]: And you also point out and there's another painting that, you know, you showed in one

00:44:04.280 --> 00:44:09.240
[Amit Varma]: of your slideshows, which is on YouTube, which I encourage people to check out, where you

00:44:09.240 --> 00:44:13.640
[Amit Varma]: showed this painting of this guy called Inayat Khan, a guy who was basically fell very ill

00:44:13.640 --> 00:44:18.680
[Amit Varma]: and was practically emaciated and, you know, literally bones jutting out and he comes to

00:44:18.680 --> 00:44:24.120
[Amit Varma]: Jahangir and ask for leave or whatever and Jahangir says fine, but first Instagram and

00:44:24.120 --> 00:44:28.440
[Amit Varma]: he summons a painter and, and that painting seems very different from all other Mughal

00:44:28.440 --> 00:44:33.000
[Amit Varma]: miniatures and all this almost like, like a Chittu Prashad painting of the Bengal famine,

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:37.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, very stark and, and this is how when you were researching this, how did you

00:44:37.400 --> 00:44:39.280
[Amit Varma]: sort of access the paintings?

00:44:39.280 --> 00:44:43.600
[Amit Varma]: Like, how do you get context of what these paintings are and what's going on here?

00:44:43.600 --> 00:44:48.800
[Guest]: Like if one of the listeners of the show wants to do that for himself, is there a way to

00:44:48.800 --> 00:44:49.800
[Guest]: do that online?

00:44:49.800 --> 00:44:52.080
[Guest]: Yeah, many of these are available online.

00:44:52.080 --> 00:44:56.360
[Guest]: If you look through, you know, through the museum, many of the museums put up their collections

00:44:56.360 --> 00:45:02.800
[Guest]: online to view and, and also Jahangir talks about some of these things in the Jahangir

00:45:02.800 --> 00:45:03.800
[Guest]: Nama.

00:45:03.800 --> 00:45:07.560
[Guest]: So this Inayat Khan story he tells, you know, so then you know that this, this painting

00:45:07.560 --> 00:45:08.560
[Guest]: exists.

00:45:08.560 --> 00:45:13.080
[Guest]: Then he talks about the zebra that comes to his court that he has, that he has painted

00:45:13.080 --> 00:45:15.080
[Guest]: and he's not sure if the stripes are real or not.

00:45:15.080 --> 00:45:18.240
[Amit Varma]: So you get someone to try and wash the stripes off.

00:45:18.240 --> 00:45:22.720
[Guest]: So you know that these paintings are there.

00:45:22.720 --> 00:45:25.520
[Guest]: So yes, I mean, there are, there are hints in the Jahangir Nama itself.

00:45:25.520 --> 00:45:32.080
[Guest]: Then of course, you know, from reading other writers, modern writers who talk about, particularly

00:45:32.080 --> 00:45:35.640
[Guest]: Ebba Koch has written about, you know, art in Jahangir's time.

00:45:35.640 --> 00:45:39.560
[Guest]: Then there's a writer called Asfar Moin who's also done a lot of very, very interesting

00:45:39.560 --> 00:45:44.360
[Guest]: sort of close readings of certain paintings made during his time.

00:45:44.360 --> 00:45:49.680
[Guest]: But I agree with you that Inayat Khan painting for me also was quite, both shocking in its

00:45:49.680 --> 00:45:56.960
[Guest]: content and in the fact that it, it is so different from anything that I have seen of,

00:45:56.960 --> 00:46:01.720
[Guest]: you know, there's something very sort of modern about it.

00:46:01.720 --> 00:46:06.360
[Guest]: You know, it seems very contemporary, it could have been made and, and, and very haunting

00:46:06.360 --> 00:46:08.360
[Guest]: and very not beautiful.

00:46:08.360 --> 00:46:11.880
[Amit Varma]: And the guy actually died shortly after the painting.

00:46:11.880 --> 00:46:15.640
[Guest]: He died the day after or something, within a day or two, he died.

00:46:15.640 --> 00:46:20.360
[Guest]: So it is, it is really, it is a representation of death.

00:46:20.360 --> 00:46:22.520
[Guest]: And it's, it's absolutely real.

00:46:22.520 --> 00:46:27.840
[Guest]: There's no, there's, there's, there's no sort of prettification, there's no, there's no

00:46:27.840 --> 00:46:28.840
[Guest]: soft edges.

00:46:28.840 --> 00:46:31.720
[Guest]: It's, it's just his.

00:46:31.720 --> 00:46:37.640
[Amit Varma]: Another very sort of interesting and endearing quality of Jahangir is sort of this endless

00:46:37.640 --> 00:46:42.680
[Amit Varma]: curiosity about the natural world, which made me feel a little ashamed because, you know,

00:46:42.680 --> 00:46:47.800
[Amit Varma]: I don't know if it's true of you, but I feel jaded about a lot of things, the wonder and

00:46:47.800 --> 00:46:51.840
[Amit Varma]: awe of, you know, discovering new things and seeing something for the first time.

00:46:51.840 --> 00:46:54.040
[Amit Varma]: And just wondering how does that work?

00:46:54.040 --> 00:46:55.400
[Amit Varma]: It's just not there in me anymore.

00:46:55.400 --> 00:46:58.440
[Amit Varma]: And you'd imagine a Mughal emperor would be far more jaded.

00:46:58.440 --> 00:47:05.560
[Amit Varma]: And yet you have him telling his men to milk a lion, because he wants to see how that processes,

00:47:05.560 --> 00:47:07.520
[Amit Varma]: you have the snake and the rabbit story.

00:47:07.520 --> 00:47:13.360
[Amit Varma]: There's another story where he finds two different kinds of goats, you pointed out, and he gets

00:47:13.360 --> 00:47:16.640
[Amit Varma]: them to mate because he wants to see what will come out of it at the same time using

00:47:16.640 --> 00:47:19.880
[Amit Varma]: that I'm sure they would be tasty.

00:47:19.880 --> 00:47:25.040
[Amit Varma]: And you know, there's another story about how a dog gives bites an elephant and the

00:47:25.040 --> 00:47:26.360
[Amit Varma]: elephant dies of rabies.

00:47:26.360 --> 00:47:31.280
[Amit Varma]: And Jahangir is like, yeah, there's something there, but he doesn't really explore it further.

00:47:31.280 --> 00:47:34.960
[Amit Varma]: But how can something so small attack something so big?

00:47:34.960 --> 00:47:40.400
[Amit Varma]: And my another story that actually ranks up there with the snake and the rabbit story

00:47:40.400 --> 00:47:43.000
[Amit Varma]: is my favorite is a lion and the goat story.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:48.480
[Amit Varma]: Where Khosrow's son, the Dabar Baksh gives him, you know, a lion and a goat who are coexisting

00:47:48.480 --> 00:47:50.320
[Amit Varma]: in a cage.

00:47:50.320 --> 00:47:53.120
[Amit Varma]: And he's curious about what kind of lion is this?

00:47:53.120 --> 00:47:54.840
[Amit Varma]: Will this work with any other goat?

00:47:54.840 --> 00:47:59.480
[Amit Varma]: He gets a goat taken out, look like goat is put in, immediately killed, puts in a sheep,

00:47:59.480 --> 00:48:00.760
[Amit Varma]: immediately killed.

00:48:00.760 --> 00:48:05.120
[Amit Varma]: And then the same goat is put back in and the lion treats it warmly and starts cuddling

00:48:05.120 --> 00:48:06.120
[Amit Varma]: up with it.

00:48:06.120 --> 00:48:10.920
[Guest]: Yeah, it's just amazing the stories from his time.

00:48:10.920 --> 00:48:16.440
[Guest]: And he does that I think his curiosity is one of the most endearing things about him.

00:48:16.440 --> 00:48:22.560
[Guest]: Without his curiosity, you know, he would be he would not because there are very I mean,

00:48:22.560 --> 00:48:29.440
[Guest]: he has terrible, terrible cruelties and terrible sort of, I mean, there are many things about

00:48:29.440 --> 00:48:31.200
[Guest]: him that are not attractive.

00:48:31.200 --> 00:48:37.280
[Guest]: But this this is real appreciation of beauty and his boundless curiosity, like you said,

00:48:37.280 --> 00:48:42.920
[Guest]: really make him and make his Jhangir Nama both so compelling, you know, as both as a

00:48:42.920 --> 00:48:45.120
[Guest]: man and as a book.

00:48:45.120 --> 00:48:48.640
[Guest]: And I think in one sense, I suppose you get, you know, reading it, the other thing you

00:48:48.640 --> 00:48:53.480
[Guest]: realize is that the world was far less known at that time, you know, things were still

00:48:53.480 --> 00:48:54.480
[Guest]: new.

00:48:54.480 --> 00:49:01.320
[Guest]: You know, I mean, atlases and maps and globes were still like new things.

00:49:01.320 --> 00:49:08.480
[Guest]: And you know, there's this story of about Thomas Rowe, in fact, and at some point, Thomas

00:49:08.480 --> 00:49:13.080
[Guest]: Rowe presents Jhangir with an atlas.

00:49:13.080 --> 00:49:17.280
[Guest]: And at first, Jhangir is quite curious about it.

00:49:17.280 --> 00:49:20.240
[Guest]: And then he sends it back within a couple of days.

00:49:20.240 --> 00:49:27.240
[Guest]: And Thomas Rowe realizes that the reason he's done this is because, you know, in those atlases

00:49:27.240 --> 00:49:32.560
[Guest]: and even now in an atlas, as they're made, India appears much smaller than Europe, you

00:49:32.560 --> 00:49:37.360
[Guest]: know, so he doesn't doesn't like the idea of his kingdom being smaller than any.

00:49:37.360 --> 00:49:40.720
[Guest]: He's the emperor of the world, you know.

00:49:40.720 --> 00:49:43.320
[Guest]: So, so the world is not fully known.

00:49:43.320 --> 00:49:49.360
[Guest]: There's this amazing little bit where one of these other British Englishmen in his court

00:49:49.360 --> 00:49:53.440
[Guest]: is William Hawkins, who spent about four or five years there.

00:49:53.440 --> 00:49:57.000
[Guest]: And he he's come his last voyage was in the West Indies.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:59.080
[Guest]: And Jhangir says to him, you know, I've heard of the West Indies.

00:49:59.080 --> 00:50:02.040
[Guest]: I wasn't sure if it was a real place.

00:50:02.040 --> 00:50:03.680
[Guest]: You know, I wasn't sure if it actually existed.

00:50:03.680 --> 00:50:04.680
[Guest]: What is it?

00:50:04.680 --> 00:50:07.000
[Guest]: And so, you know, so he tells him all about it.

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:13.520
[Guest]: And even, forget Jhangir, there's this Italian chap who's coming to India, Pietro Della

00:50:13.520 --> 00:50:14.520
[Guest]: Valle.

00:50:14.520 --> 00:50:17.280
[Guest]: And he's coming and on the way, you know, he talks about how he and the captain are

00:50:17.280 --> 00:50:19.280
[Guest]: discussing unicorns.

00:50:19.280 --> 00:50:21.360
[Guest]: And they're not discussing whether or not unicorns exist.

00:50:21.360 --> 00:50:24.760
[Guest]: They're discussing on which latitude and longitude unicorns are found.

00:50:24.760 --> 00:50:33.160
[Guest]: So the world is far more wonderful in some ways and full of wonder than it is today.

00:50:33.160 --> 00:50:35.920
[Guest]: There's things still to be discovered.

00:50:35.920 --> 00:50:40.320
[Guest]: And that said, you know, it can also be very frustrating sometimes when you're reading

00:50:40.320 --> 00:50:46.320
[Guest]: what Jhangir and his curiosities, because the curiosity stops and it stops almost as

00:50:46.320 --> 00:50:48.400
[Guest]: if there's this blind spot.

00:50:48.400 --> 00:50:54.360
[Guest]: You know, like the thing you mentioned about the dog who gives, infects the elephant, right?

00:50:54.360 --> 00:51:00.120
[Guest]: And Jhangir is like, oh, how can such a small creature make such a large creature ill?

00:51:00.120 --> 00:51:08.520
[Guest]: And I just want to sort of shout out to him across the centuries, this is how infection

00:51:08.520 --> 00:51:09.520
[Guest]: works.

00:51:09.520 --> 00:51:10.520
[Guest]: You know, this is malaria.

00:51:10.520 --> 00:51:14.400
[Amit Varma]: There's literally no way he can have the intellectual tools.

00:51:14.400 --> 00:51:15.960
[Guest]: There's no way, exactly.

00:51:15.960 --> 00:51:22.400
[Guest]: So you realize how much has changed, you know, how easy it is for us to make that connection

00:51:22.400 --> 00:51:25.960
[Guest]: and how almost impossible it is for him.

00:51:25.960 --> 00:51:31.600
[Guest]: Or even when, you know, there's another point of meteor, meteor falls somewhere nearby in

00:51:31.600 --> 00:51:39.200
[Guest]: Jalandhar and everyone is very excited, of course, and Jhangir wants to see this metal.

00:51:39.200 --> 00:51:41.200
[Guest]: But again, there's this sort of curtain that falls.

00:51:41.200 --> 00:51:48.600
[Guest]: It's not, you know, beyond sort of making some knives and swords out of it.

00:51:48.600 --> 00:51:53.280
[Guest]: There's no interrogation of what is this, where does it come from?

00:51:53.280 --> 00:51:59.400
[Guest]: You know, even though astrology and astronomy are both sort of the highly developed skills

00:51:59.400 --> 00:52:06.200
[Guest]: and passions at the time, natural meteor falling, just somehow you can, it's there it is.

00:52:06.200 --> 00:52:10.440
[Guest]: You make your sword out of it and then it's finished.

00:52:10.440 --> 00:52:12.360
[Guest]: It's just a full stop.

00:52:12.360 --> 00:52:16.240
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you quote an Englishman named Henry Beveridge saying that Jhangir would have been

00:52:16.240 --> 00:52:21.360
[Amit Varma]: a better and happier man as a head of a natural history museum, rather than, you know, an

00:52:21.360 --> 00:52:22.360
[Amit Varma]: imperial emperor.

00:52:22.360 --> 00:52:27.280
[Amit Varma]: Tell me also about, I mean, I mean, you know, you live in Delhi and we keep talking about

00:52:27.280 --> 00:52:29.640
[Amit Varma]: the air quality index of Delhi and all that.

00:52:29.640 --> 00:52:35.080
[Amit Varma]: How many people know that Jhangir was one of the pioneers of air quality index?

00:52:35.080 --> 00:52:39.120
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about his efforts at measuring pollution in Gujarat.

00:52:39.120 --> 00:52:41.440
[Guest]: Yeah, so he went to Gujarat.

00:52:41.440 --> 00:52:46.400
[Guest]: He had been in Mandu for a while and he'd really enjoyed it.

00:52:46.400 --> 00:52:50.960
[Guest]: And he then he was going up to Ahmedabad and he'd heard a great, great thing about Ahmedabad.

00:52:50.960 --> 00:52:56.120
[Guest]: He'd heard of, he was looking forward to going there.

00:52:56.120 --> 00:53:00.360
[Guest]: And he arrived and immediately, almost immediately, he begins to complain.

00:53:00.360 --> 00:53:01.880
[Guest]: He said, you know, what is this place?

00:53:01.880 --> 00:53:03.560
[Guest]: It's a dust heap, he calls it.

00:53:03.560 --> 00:53:06.960
[Guest]: And he says the air is just poisonous.

00:53:06.960 --> 00:53:10.360
[Guest]: And he can't leave because there's a plague that's broken out in Agra.

00:53:10.360 --> 00:53:14.480
[Guest]: So he can't go back to Agra and he's just more or less trapped.

00:53:14.480 --> 00:53:17.080
[Guest]: And Ahmedabad, he falls ill.

00:53:17.080 --> 00:53:18.080
[Guest]: He has to eat khichdi.

00:53:18.080 --> 00:53:20.120
[Guest]: He says, I've not eaten khichdi since I was a child.

00:53:20.120 --> 00:53:23.240
[Guest]: And I really had hoped I would never have to eat it again.

00:53:23.240 --> 00:53:26.120
[Guest]: But here I am.

00:53:26.120 --> 00:53:30.720
[Guest]: And so he, so anyway, to distract himself and to confirm his own theory, he orders this

00:53:30.720 --> 00:53:31.720
[Guest]: experiment.

00:53:31.720 --> 00:53:39.960
[Guest]: He has two sheep skinned and hung up, one just outside Ahmedabad and one in Mahmoodabad.

00:53:39.960 --> 00:53:40.960
[Amit Varma]: And he has...

00:53:40.960 --> 00:53:41.960
[Amit Varma]: Mahmoodabad in UP, of course.

00:53:41.960 --> 00:53:45.760
[Guest]: In UP, of course, yeah.

00:53:45.760 --> 00:53:50.120
[Guest]: And so, and the time, how long it takes for the sheep to start rotting.

00:53:50.120 --> 00:53:55.240
[Guest]: And Jahangir is very right, because the one in Ahmedabad starts to rot, I think, in eight

00:53:55.240 --> 00:53:56.880
[Guest]: hours or so.

00:53:56.880 --> 00:54:00.600
[Guest]: And the one in UP lasts six hours longer.

00:54:00.600 --> 00:54:03.840
[Guest]: And it lasts, it rots after 14 hours.

00:54:03.840 --> 00:54:10.000
[Amit Varma]: So the rotting sheep air quality index is quite...

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:15.320
[Amit Varma]: And another big nugget for my listeners, William Hawkins, who Parvati just mentioned, of course,

00:54:15.320 --> 00:54:18.640
[Amit Varma]: invented the modern pressure cooker.

00:54:18.640 --> 00:54:19.640
[Amit Varma]: I'm just kidding.

00:54:19.640 --> 00:54:20.640
[Amit Varma]: He didn't.

00:54:20.640 --> 00:54:26.200
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of, you know, you mentioned his cruelty earlier and a lot of it, you know,

00:54:26.200 --> 00:54:29.480
[Amit Varma]: at one hand, when it comes to animals, for example, of course, he has this curiosity.

00:54:29.480 --> 00:54:31.320
[Amit Varma]: He kills a snake trying to make it eat a rabbit.

00:54:31.320 --> 00:54:36.000
[Amit Varma]: But he also, for example, you mentioned how someone gives him an elephant and it's night

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:39.640
[Amit Varma]: and the elephant needs to be bathed and he's feeling bad that all the water will be too

00:54:39.640 --> 00:54:40.640
[Amit Varma]: cold.

00:54:40.640 --> 00:54:42.920
[Amit Varma]: So the water is heated for the elephant to take a bath in.

00:54:42.920 --> 00:54:45.560
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, he can be incredibly cruel.

00:54:45.560 --> 00:54:50.240
[Amit Varma]: Like one example you point out is, and we'll of course, you know, talk about Khusrow and

00:54:50.240 --> 00:54:51.600
[Amit Varma]: that whole politics later.

00:54:51.600 --> 00:54:55.280
[Amit Varma]: Khusrow is his elder son who rebels against him and he chases him.

00:54:55.280 --> 00:54:59.480
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, you know, while chasing him, he makes sacrifices like he doesn't take his

00:54:59.480 --> 00:55:00.680
[Amit Varma]: morning dose of opium.

00:55:00.680 --> 00:55:05.480
[Amit Varma]: He just runs off after Khusrow and then he reaches Lahore where there is biryani spread

00:55:05.480 --> 00:55:08.960
[Amit Varma]: out for him and he notes in the Jahangir Nama that I would have loved to have the biryani

00:55:08.960 --> 00:55:13.840
[Amit Varma]: but work awaits, possibly the only such sacrifice he made in his career.

00:55:13.840 --> 00:55:16.680
[Guest]: He has one bite per man, then he has to run.

00:55:16.680 --> 00:55:23.560
[Amit Varma]: And then he has to run after, you know, and so the cruelty, you know, the great example

00:55:23.560 --> 00:55:28.520
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, really stuck with me and I was thinking about that was of Khusrow's lieutenants,

00:55:28.520 --> 00:55:29.520
[Amit Varma]: Hussain Baig and Abdul Rahim.

00:55:29.520 --> 00:55:33.840
[Amit Varma]: And I'll quote from your book here, quote, Hussain Baig and Abdul Rahim.

00:55:33.840 --> 00:55:36.760
[Amit Varma]: This is after they've been captured and the rebellion has failed.

00:55:36.760 --> 00:55:41.480
[Amit Varma]: Quote, Hussain Baig and Abdul Rahim were wrapped naked in animal skin.

00:55:41.480 --> 00:55:46.960
[Amit Varma]: The badakshi, that's Hussain Baig, was stuffed into a freshly killed ox, Abdul Rahim into

00:55:46.960 --> 00:55:50.400
[Amit Varma]: a donkey and mounted backwards on asses.

00:55:50.400 --> 00:55:52.080
[Amit Varma]: They were paraded through the city.

00:55:52.080 --> 00:55:57.560
[Amit Varma]: Hussain Baig died of suffocation, Abdul Rahim, perhaps because donkey skin is more porous,

00:55:57.560 --> 00:56:03.280
[Amit Varma]: perhaps because he had supporters in the crowd who gave him water, survived, stop quote.

00:56:03.280 --> 00:56:07.600
[Amit Varma]: And this is one just in terms of imagination, this seems crazy.

00:56:07.600 --> 00:56:12.280
[Amit Varma]: But what also made me sort of laugh out loud was that Abdul Rahim was later reinstated

00:56:12.280 --> 00:56:16.480
[Amit Varma]: and Jahangir would call him donkey.

00:56:16.480 --> 00:56:21.240
[Amit Varma]: So and you know, and then the contrast to this is for another place you mentioned about

00:56:21.240 --> 00:56:26.000
[Amit Varma]: how he once caught fish and he released them back into the water with pearls pinned to

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:27.000
[Amit Varma]: their noses.

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:28.000
[Amit Varma]: Why was this?

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:32.000
[Guest]: God knows he was the emperor, he could do what he liked.

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:33.000
[Guest]: I really don't know.

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:34.000
[Guest]: It just was.

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:41.880
[Guest]: Actually, that was one of those moments that struck me, you know, as as because some of

00:56:41.880 --> 00:56:46.560
[Guest]: the reading of the Jahangir and getting to sort of know him as much as possible to, you

00:56:46.560 --> 00:56:54.400
[Guest]: know, know a character from history was getting to know what it is to have almost limitless

00:56:54.400 --> 00:57:00.640
[Guest]: power, you know, and you and you start asking yourself in the course of it, like, if I had

00:57:00.640 --> 00:57:02.840
[Guest]: this kind of power, what would I do?

00:57:02.840 --> 00:57:05.040
[Guest]: And would I not go a little mad?

00:57:05.040 --> 00:57:08.080
[Guest]: You know, and I think it would be almost impossible not to.

00:57:08.080 --> 00:57:15.200
[Guest]: So so if you have the power to release fish with pearls in their noses, I suppose why

00:57:15.200 --> 00:57:16.200
[Amit Varma]: not?

00:57:16.200 --> 00:57:17.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I think so.

00:57:17.200 --> 00:57:19.840
[Amit Varma]: And there is there is also the sense, as you point out, that there are parts of the book

00:57:19.840 --> 00:57:24.400
[Amit Varma]: where even Jahangir is surprised by the extent of his own power, such as when he's in court

00:57:24.400 --> 00:57:28.200
[Amit Varma]: and a supplicant comes and says that I want to marry this widow, can you please persuade

00:57:28.200 --> 00:57:29.200
[Amit Varma]: her?

00:57:29.200 --> 00:57:32.680
[Amit Varma]: Then the guy says that I would jump from the highest tower to show my love and Jahangir

00:57:32.680 --> 00:57:33.840
[Amit Varma]: says, OK, jump from there.

00:57:33.840 --> 00:57:37.160
[Amit Varma]: And he points to a nearby thing and the guy runs and he jumps and dies.

00:57:37.160 --> 00:57:39.400
[Amit Varma]: And Jahangir is like, what have what just happened?

00:57:39.400 --> 00:57:42.160
[Amit Varma]: You know, and that is the power of the emperor.

00:57:42.160 --> 00:57:50.480
[Amit Varma]: So how can it and despite that it you know, it's very hard one power because, you know,

00:57:50.480 --> 00:57:52.840
[Amit Varma]: before he becomes emperor, which is not a done deal.

00:57:52.840 --> 00:57:56.920
[Amit Varma]: And we've already sort of discussed about both how he, Murad and Daniyal, the three

00:57:56.920 --> 00:57:59.160
[Amit Varma]: brothers were disappointments to their father.

00:57:59.160 --> 00:58:03.760
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, when he was pissed off at Jahangir, Akbar looked at Murad and then later Murad

00:58:03.760 --> 00:58:09.680
[Amit Varma]: died of drink and he looked at Daniyal and Daniyal also died of drink in a fairly crazy

00:58:09.680 --> 00:58:10.680
[Amit Varma]: incident.

00:58:10.680 --> 00:58:15.000
[Amit Varma]: And then he turns to his grandchildren and he looks at Jahangir's sons.

00:58:15.000 --> 00:58:19.800
[Amit Varma]: And in particular, Khosrow is a person, Khosrow is about 17 or 18 at the time.

00:58:19.800 --> 00:58:22.520
[Amit Varma]: And he's thinking of propping him up.

00:58:22.520 --> 00:58:24.320
[Amit Varma]: And what's that rivalry like?

00:58:24.320 --> 00:58:29.200
[Guest]: Well, I mean, you know, I don't know, but I can only imagine what it must have been

00:58:29.200 --> 00:58:30.200
[Guest]: like.

00:58:30.200 --> 00:58:33.200
[Guest]: Because again, there are only hints, you know, for this.

00:58:33.200 --> 00:58:39.040
[Guest]: Like, you know, Abul Fazal says, for example, cryptically, that the emperor always preferred

00:58:39.040 --> 00:58:42.800
[Guest]: his grandsons to his sons.

00:58:42.800 --> 00:58:49.400
[Guest]: And there's also, you know, just this, just a sort of stray fact that Akbar's grandsons

00:58:49.400 --> 00:58:52.960
[Guest]: called him Shah Baba, you know, King Father.

00:58:52.960 --> 00:58:58.400
[Guest]: And their father, Jahangir was Shahbhai, the king brother.

00:58:58.400 --> 00:59:06.040
[Guest]: So this sort of hierarchy was very clearly, you know, the power was very clearly flowing

00:59:06.040 --> 00:59:12.840
[Guest]: down from Akbar down to everyone below was sort of on a similar plane.

00:59:12.840 --> 00:59:19.680
[Guest]: And so what it must have been like for Jahangir, I mean, it certainly it couldn't have been

00:59:19.680 --> 00:59:27.240
[Guest]: easy to have to know that, you know, your own son is preferred over you for the throne.

00:59:27.240 --> 00:59:35.600
[Guest]: And but it's not so much through him that we get to see how much tension there must

00:59:35.600 --> 00:59:36.600
[Guest]: have been.

00:59:36.600 --> 00:59:42.960
[Guest]: But through, you know, Khosrow's poor mother, who's Manbhai, who's also Man Singh's sister

00:59:42.960 --> 00:59:45.880
[Guest]: and Jahangir's first wife.

00:59:45.880 --> 00:59:50.520
[Guest]: And at some point, she commits suicide.

00:59:50.520 --> 00:59:53.360
[Guest]: She overdoses on opium and dies.

00:59:53.360 --> 00:59:55.520
[Guest]: And Jahangir writes about it again in the Jahangir Nama.

00:59:55.520 --> 00:59:58.360
[Guest]: And he says, and he blames Khosrow.

00:59:58.360 --> 01:00:04.280
[Guest]: He says, you know, she was so upset with Khosrow because he was behaving badly that she couldn't

01:00:04.280 --> 01:00:06.760
[Guest]: take it and she killed herself.

01:00:06.760 --> 01:00:14.800
[Guest]: And meanwhile, in the Akbar Nama, the blame falls squarely on Jahangir because, you know,

01:00:14.800 --> 01:00:21.920
[Guest]: the Akbar Nama says that Jahangir treated her so badly and upset her so much that she

01:00:21.920 --> 01:00:22.920
[Guest]: killed herself.

01:00:22.920 --> 01:00:29.000
[Guest]: And of course, there's also the theory and the suggestion that she and in the family,

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:33.040
[Guest]: there was a kind of manic depression that ran in the family.

01:00:33.040 --> 01:00:37.240
[Guest]: So, you know, she may also have been suffering from a depression of some sort, but still

01:00:37.240 --> 01:00:39.880
[Guest]: there would, you know, there would have to be triggered.

01:00:39.880 --> 01:00:43.920
[Guest]: And so it certainly can't have been fun.

01:00:43.920 --> 01:00:49.320
[Guest]: And you know, it's obviously an increasingly, increasingly dysfunctional family.

01:00:49.320 --> 01:00:54.280
[Amit Varma]: Your husband is fighting with your son who is backed by your father-in-law.

01:00:54.280 --> 01:00:58.280
[Guest]: For the throne, for the empire of all Hindustan.

01:00:58.280 --> 01:01:02.240
[Amit Varma]: And just again, you know, as we learn from Thomas Rose's writings, and I think William

01:01:02.240 --> 01:01:06.760
[Amit Varma]: Hawkins, inventor of the pressure cooker, estimated that while the Mughal Empire was

01:01:06.760 --> 01:01:10.440
[Amit Varma]: worth 56 million, England was half a million.

01:01:10.440 --> 01:01:11.440
[Amit Varma]: So that was a difference.

01:01:11.440 --> 01:01:12.800
[Amit Varma]: This was a mighty empire.

01:01:12.800 --> 01:01:13.880
[Amit Varma]: There was a lot at stake.

01:01:13.880 --> 01:01:18.480
[Amit Varma]: And also within Mughal dynasties, the way succession worked is it didn't automatically

01:01:18.480 --> 01:01:21.840
[Amit Varma]: go to the eldest son, like it does in some dynasties.

01:01:21.840 --> 01:01:23.800
[Amit Varma]: You know, there weren't any rules like that.

01:01:23.800 --> 01:01:25.360
[Amit Varma]: So it was up for grabs.

01:01:25.360 --> 01:01:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And of course, in Akbar's times, it was relatively gentle.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:32.960
[Amit Varma]: The worst you might do what Jahangir at one point did to Khosrow was blind him because

01:01:32.960 --> 01:01:36.240
[Amit Varma]: blind people, according to Islam, cannot ascend the throne.

01:01:36.240 --> 01:01:39.280
[Amit Varma]: But Shah Jahan basically just killed off all contenders.

01:01:39.280 --> 01:01:47.440
[Amit Varma]: And that sort of became more and more vicious, you know, one sort of counterfactual, if you'll

01:01:47.440 --> 01:01:52.440
[Amit Varma]: sort of indulge me in this is what I've always wondered is one, it seems clear to me that

01:01:52.440 --> 01:01:58.920
[Amit Varma]: Khosrow was admired and idolized by a lot of people possibly seems to be have been a

01:01:58.920 --> 01:02:03.520
[Amit Varma]: lot more powerful than Jahangir and certainly had the support of all the women in the court,

01:02:03.520 --> 01:02:08.600
[Amit Varma]: all the sisters and mothers and aunts who are so powerful and was respected by them

01:02:08.600 --> 01:02:14.080
[Amit Varma]: and feared by his own brother Khurram, the later Shah Jahan, who had him sort of put

01:02:14.080 --> 01:02:19.000
[Amit Varma]: to death and Khosrow, you could say had numerous chances to ascend to the throne one directly

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:25.000
[Amit Varma]: after Akbar or two just as Jahangir's son after Jahangir.

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:30.040
[Amit Varma]: And you know, he got like many second, there were many second acts in his life, and none

01:02:30.040 --> 01:02:31.840
[Amit Varma]: of them worked out.

01:02:31.840 --> 01:02:36.520
[Amit Varma]: The counterfactual here is that what if Khosrow does become emperor, and therefore neither

01:02:36.520 --> 01:02:40.600
[Amit Varma]: Jahangir nor Shah Jahan ever kind of become emperor.

01:02:40.600 --> 01:02:43.560
[Amit Varma]: Is there a drastic difference to history?

01:02:43.560 --> 01:02:48.040
[Amit Varma]: Or would you expect the rest of Indian history to proceed along?

01:02:48.040 --> 01:02:51.280
[Amit Varma]: Indirectly, what I'm asking you is what do you feel about say Thomas Carlyle's great

01:02:51.280 --> 01:02:55.960
[Amit Varma]: man theory of history, which I assume you would say that look, Akbar certainly was a

01:02:55.960 --> 01:02:58.920
[Amit Varma]: great man without him, India's history is completely different.

01:02:58.920 --> 01:03:01.120
[Amit Varma]: Who could have built this empire?

01:03:01.120 --> 01:03:06.120
[Amit Varma]: But you know, I look at Khosrow and I think that no one talks of Khosrow, but he was so

01:03:06.120 --> 01:03:07.680
[Amit Varma]: close.

01:03:07.680 --> 01:03:12.600
[Amit Varma]: And had he gotten it, you know, Jahangir and Shah Jahan and therefore Aurangzeb later might

01:03:12.600 --> 01:03:14.720
[Amit Varma]: never have been emperors.

01:03:14.720 --> 01:03:16.080
[Amit Varma]: Is that something you've thought about?

01:03:16.080 --> 01:03:21.680
[Guest]: I haven't thought much, although you can't help feeling sorry for Khosrow if you read

01:03:21.680 --> 01:03:22.680
[Guest]: about him.

01:03:22.680 --> 01:03:23.680
[Guest]: Of course, he really does.

01:03:23.680 --> 01:03:24.920
[Guest]: He's so close.

01:03:24.920 --> 01:03:26.400
[Guest]: And he has such powerful support.

01:03:26.400 --> 01:03:32.080
[Guest]: I mean, he has the support, probably possibly of his own grandfather, Akbar.

01:03:32.080 --> 01:03:39.240
[Guest]: And he certainly has the support of Man Singh, his uncle, and his father in law, Mirza Aziz

01:03:39.240 --> 01:03:44.680
[Guest]: Koka, who is Akbar's one of his closest, closest friends, advisors and his foster brother.

01:03:44.680 --> 01:03:48.040
[Amit Varma]: And Man Singh, of course, was a governor of Bengal and perhaps one of the best generals

01:03:48.040 --> 01:03:49.040
[Guest]: of the Mughal Empire.

01:03:49.040 --> 01:03:50.040
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:03:50.040 --> 01:03:52.760
[Guest]: So he had this powerful backing.

01:03:52.760 --> 01:03:58.520
[Guest]: And then suddenly to have that snatched away, and then to be so clear in your own mind that

01:03:58.520 --> 01:04:05.200
[Guest]: you deserve the throne more than your father does, that you then within six months, rebel.

01:04:05.200 --> 01:04:09.840
[Guest]: And you know, he gets this, he gets enough support.

01:04:09.840 --> 01:04:15.320
[Guest]: And yet he has terrible luck, and he clearly doesn't have as much experience in sort of

01:04:15.320 --> 01:04:17.200
[Guest]: leading a rebellion.

01:04:17.200 --> 01:04:19.640
[Guest]: So he's captured.

01:04:19.640 --> 01:04:25.920
[Guest]: And as you said, his general meet this sort of gruesome punishment and the rest of them.

01:04:25.920 --> 01:04:30.760
[Guest]: I mean, you know, he, Khosrow himself, is made to ride on sort of an emaciated elephant

01:04:30.760 --> 01:04:32.360
[Guest]: through the gates of Lahore.

01:04:32.360 --> 01:04:37.200
[Guest]: And on either side of him, you know, hundreds of his supporters are impaired.

01:04:37.200 --> 01:04:44.400
[Guest]: So you know, dying gruesomely on either side of the road as he walks, marches past them.

01:04:44.400 --> 01:04:48.360
[Guest]: And yet the same chap, I mean, obviously had some degree of charisma and appeal because

01:04:48.360 --> 01:04:54.960
[Guest]: within again, a year or so, maybe a few months, he's managed to ferment another, you know,

01:04:54.960 --> 01:05:00.120
[Guest]: rebellion, which is when sort of Jahangir has him blinded.

01:05:00.120 --> 01:05:02.640
[Guest]: Though even that is possibly was a reversible blinding.

01:05:02.640 --> 01:05:09.080
[Guest]: And because the eyes, the eyelids are sewn together, and then they can be opened.

01:05:09.080 --> 01:05:10.080
[Amit Varma]: That's convenient.

01:05:10.080 --> 01:05:13.800
[Amit Varma]: So if he changes his mind, if he changes his mind, yeah.

01:05:13.800 --> 01:05:19.600
[Guest]: So there's some accounts that say that he, you know, at some point he was, his eyes were

01:05:19.600 --> 01:05:23.080
[Guest]: opening yet, which is why he remained a threat to Khurram.

01:05:23.080 --> 01:05:28.840
[Guest]: You know, otherwise, if he had been really blind, then Khurram need not have...

01:05:28.840 --> 01:05:34.280
[Amit Varma]: No, and one of the anecdotes, which was really striking, and which made me think a little

01:05:34.280 --> 01:05:37.800
[Amit Varma]: harder about Khosrow, what kind of man he must have been, is that you point out that

01:05:37.800 --> 01:05:42.040
[Amit Varma]: much later in life, when, you know, Noor Jehan is a very powerful figure, and we'll talk

01:05:42.040 --> 01:05:43.480
[Amit Varma]: about that a little while later.

01:05:43.480 --> 01:05:48.680
[Amit Varma]: But what essentially, so she was married earlier to this guy called Sher Afghan, I think, and

01:05:48.680 --> 01:05:51.240
[Amit Varma]: she had a daughter through Sher Afghan.

01:05:51.240 --> 01:05:55.520
[Amit Varma]: And she was thinking of getting that daughter married to Khosrow, which would immediately

01:05:55.520 --> 01:05:58.200
[Amit Varma]: make him a contender for the throne again.

01:05:58.200 --> 01:06:02.080
[Amit Varma]: And Khosrow refused, because he wanted to be loyal to his wife.

01:06:02.080 --> 01:06:04.880
[Amit Varma]: And his wife said that, No, no, this is good for you.

01:06:04.880 --> 01:06:08.080
[Amit Varma]: This will finally get us out of the wilderness, you could be emperor.

01:06:08.080 --> 01:06:10.360
[Amit Varma]: And he said, No, I'm not going to do it.

01:06:10.360 --> 01:06:12.160
[Amit Varma]: And this blew my mind, who does this?

01:06:12.160 --> 01:06:17.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, when it's so commonplace for these guys to have multiple sort of...

01:06:17.000 --> 01:06:20.520
[Guest]: Yeah, although this is a story that is told.

01:06:20.520 --> 01:06:26.320
[Guest]: So you know, it's possible he did, it seems like very foolish of him, if he did do that.

01:06:26.320 --> 01:06:29.920
[Guest]: But it's also possible that he disliked Noor Deha very much, who knows, you know, maybe

01:06:29.920 --> 01:06:34.400
[Guest]: he didn't trust her, maybe he didn't, you know, because it was, it was difficult.

01:06:34.400 --> 01:06:38.120
[Guest]: But, but all he just made the very wrong choice.

01:06:38.120 --> 01:06:40.760
[Guest]: But but you know, to come back to what you're saying about what would have happened if he

01:06:40.760 --> 01:06:50.040
[Guest]: had been, if he, I don't know, I think, to me, if you look at how the empire first grows

01:06:50.040 --> 01:06:57.240
[Guest]: and then sort of collapses upon itself, you know, succession is, of course, one part of

01:06:57.240 --> 01:06:58.240
[Guest]: it.

01:06:58.240 --> 01:07:02.880
[Guest]: But and this idea that there's no primogeniture amongst the Mughals, so there isn't, you know,

01:07:02.880 --> 01:07:06.800
[Guest]: but there was, it's not like there wasn't a system and the system would be to sort of

01:07:06.800 --> 01:07:11.320
[Guest]: divide the empire amongst different heirs.

01:07:11.320 --> 01:07:15.000
[Guest]: And you know, one of the most interesting things that I've been reading, I've been reading

01:07:15.000 --> 01:07:20.320
[Guest]: about Humayun a little bit in the last few months, and you know, there is this suggestion

01:07:20.320 --> 01:07:25.360
[Guest]: that towards the end of his reign, Babur was beginning to feel about Humayun very much

01:07:25.360 --> 01:07:30.960
[Guest]: as Akbar was feeling about Jahangir, that the staff was not up to it, you know, that

01:07:30.960 --> 01:07:34.400
[Guest]: so he didn't want to, he was anyway he had parceled out, I think he had given Kabul to

01:07:34.400 --> 01:07:40.140
[Guest]: Kamran and I think perhaps Lahore and Punjab to Askari.

01:07:40.140 --> 01:07:46.560
[Guest]: And he was he wanted to send Humayun to Badakhshan, but Humayun was posted there, he was not supposed

01:07:46.560 --> 01:07:55.040
[Guest]: to be in Delhi, and Delhi and Agra would go to Babur's brother in law, who was married

01:07:55.040 --> 01:08:02.120
[Guest]: to his sister Khanzada Begum, who is one of the most memorable characters in that family.

01:08:02.120 --> 01:08:03.880
[Guest]: And she was very close to her.

01:08:03.880 --> 01:08:08.240
[Guest]: So the suggestion is that in fact, he was going to make his sister, in a sense, the

01:08:08.240 --> 01:08:09.240
[Amit Varma]: de facto Empress.

01:08:09.240 --> 01:08:14.640
[Guest]: The Empress of this part of the empire, you know, and then they would sort of share and

01:08:14.640 --> 01:08:20.440
[Guest]: then even under Akbar, I mean, Akbar becomes emperor of whatever little bit Humayun has

01:08:20.440 --> 01:08:22.200
[Guest]: managed to get back.

01:08:22.200 --> 01:08:26.960
[Guest]: His younger brother, Muhammad Hakim is in Kabul and he is sort of he and his mother

01:08:26.960 --> 01:08:31.240
[Guest]: are the rulers of Kabul and Kabul remains a kind of autonomous region, even though you

01:08:31.240 --> 01:08:36.800
[Guest]: know, Hakim rebels once or twice and Akbar sends in an army, but until he dies, Akbar

01:08:36.800 --> 01:08:42.120
[Guest]: doesn't make Kabul into one of, you know, part of the empire.

01:08:42.120 --> 01:08:45.560
[Guest]: But then, you know, the empire just expands and expands and expands.

01:08:45.560 --> 01:08:54.040
[Guest]: And so then does the lure of it, you know, so by the time you come to Shah Jahan and

01:08:54.040 --> 01:09:03.080
[Guest]: then to Aurangzeb, the stakes are so high that and the greed also then, you know, it

01:09:03.080 --> 01:09:10.280
[Guest]: multiplies by leaps and bounds and so does the venality and the murderous impulses.

01:09:10.280 --> 01:09:17.120
[Guest]: So you know, unless Khosrow had lost the empire, he had to begin again from scratch.

01:09:17.120 --> 01:09:23.400
[Guest]: If he had been as successful as Jahangir was and there's no, it's not necessary that he

01:09:23.400 --> 01:09:27.600
[Guest]: might or might not have been because Jahangir, I don't think would have taken it lying down.

01:09:27.600 --> 01:09:33.680
[Guest]: And he would have had a he did have a very strong support, you know, and he would have

01:09:33.680 --> 01:09:35.920
[Guest]: he would have attracted support also.

01:09:35.920 --> 01:09:40.440
[Guest]: He was not bad at creating alliances and drawing people to him.

01:09:40.440 --> 01:09:46.720
[Amit Varma]: In fact, one of the interesting things that, you know, after he won the battle of succession,

01:09:46.720 --> 01:09:50.840
[Amit Varma]: which I'll ask you about, one of the things he did was he forgave many of the people who

01:09:50.840 --> 01:09:55.360
[Amit Varma]: were against him, you know, almost like, you know, Lincoln and the team of rival things

01:09:55.360 --> 01:10:00.320
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, he forgave all these people, even in the example of, you know, Abdul Rahim,

01:10:00.320 --> 01:10:05.840
[Amit Varma]: who was stuffed in donkey skin and paraded through, but ultimately back in the court.

01:10:05.840 --> 01:10:08.400
[Amit Varma]: So he was obviously a very interesting kind of statesman.

01:10:08.400 --> 01:10:10.000
[Amit Varma]: He wasn't completely incompetent.

01:10:10.000 --> 01:10:14.000
[Amit Varma]: He was making his sort of alliances and stuff.

