[Unknown]: On GayBCD, Sunetra and Farah talk about how they face discrimination as kids for choosing

01:12:34.180 --> 01:12:36.200
[Unknown]: to do things against gender norms.

01:12:36.200 --> 01:12:40.160
[Unknown]: On Postcards from Nowhere, Utsav, who is on Cyrus this week if you have forgotten, talks

01:12:40.160 --> 01:12:43.560
[Unknown]: about witnessing Kerala's famous martial art, Kelari Pattu.

01:12:43.560 --> 01:12:46.440
[Unknown]: And with that, let's get you on with your show.

01:12:46.440 --> 01:12:47.680
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

01:12:47.680 --> 01:12:52.480
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Parvati Sharma, the author of an entertaining biography of Jehangir and

01:12:52.480 --> 01:12:57.220
[Amit Varma]: entertaining why not just because of the delightful style of writing, but also because history

01:12:57.220 --> 01:12:58.440
[Amit Varma]: is entertaining.

01:12:58.440 --> 01:12:59.640
[Amit Varma]: These are incredible stories.

01:12:59.640 --> 01:13:01.440
[Amit Varma]: You can't make this shit up.

01:13:01.440 --> 01:13:06.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, while we were at the break, you sort of told me that, you know, you went back

01:13:06.560 --> 01:13:10.920
[Amit Varma]: to my earlier question about how ordinary people lived in the Mughal Empire, because

01:13:10.920 --> 01:13:11.920
[Amit Varma]: what do they do?

01:13:11.920 --> 01:13:14.840
[Amit Varma]: They don't get up in the morning and look at their smartphone and complain about the

01:13:14.840 --> 01:13:15.840
[Amit Varma]: battery.

01:13:15.840 --> 01:13:21.360
[Amit Varma]: So, so tell me a bit about, you know, what insights you gained on that from reading the

01:13:21.360 --> 01:13:22.360
[Amit Varma]: literature of this period.

01:13:22.360 --> 01:13:27.840
[Guest]: No, so there was, you know, it wasn't so much insight as just these sometimes these really

01:13:27.840 --> 01:13:37.080
[Guest]: vivid glimpses of moments in everyday life, you know, and, you know, amongst them, for

01:13:37.080 --> 01:13:40.640
[Guest]: example, and many of them come from the sort of European writers, because they are the

01:13:40.640 --> 01:13:47.040
[Guest]: ones who, you know, recording what it is to live every day or to the sites that they see

01:13:47.040 --> 01:13:49.400
[Guest]: for their audiences back home.

01:13:49.400 --> 01:13:56.520
[Guest]: So, you know, somebody, one of them very bitterly, in fact, writes about how, you know, people

01:13:56.520 --> 01:14:02.760
[Guest]: in some villages, he sees women and children wearing necklaces of, of clothes, you know,

01:14:02.760 --> 01:14:05.660
[Guest]: because clothes are so, so, so cheap here.

01:14:05.660 --> 01:14:12.440
[Guest]: And this poor man is trying to, he's a Dutch trader and he's bringing spices from the Spice

01:14:12.440 --> 01:14:18.840
[Guest]: Islands to India, but you know, he's not able to make very much money for what he brings.

01:14:18.840 --> 01:14:21.760
[Guest]: And he has to spend more than he has on what he needs to buy.

01:14:21.760 --> 01:14:26.200
[Guest]: Or you have, you know, another, another writer who arrives in Gujarat.

01:14:26.200 --> 01:14:30.000
[Guest]: So he's writing about Cambe and then about Surat.

01:14:30.000 --> 01:14:36.040
[Guest]: And he presents this very dynamic view of these, you know, bustling cities with these

01:14:36.040 --> 01:14:40.800
[Guest]: bullock carts racing through the streets with, you know, the bells on the, on the necks of

01:14:40.800 --> 01:14:45.800
[Guest]: the, of the, of the bulls ringing loudly to, to alert everyone.

01:14:45.800 --> 01:14:49.840
[Guest]: He talks about hospital, animal hospitals, you know, and hospital, I mean, obviously

01:14:49.840 --> 01:14:55.920
[Guest]: for larger animals like gaushalas and all, but also hospitals for, for mice and for birds

01:14:55.920 --> 01:15:03.360
[Guest]: and you know, and, and he presents also this, you know, picture of, of, you know, tanks

01:15:03.360 --> 01:15:09.760
[Guest]: built at regular intervals as, you know, water or access to water is something that is provided

01:15:09.760 --> 01:15:17.360
[Guest]: as a philanthropic act by the richer people in a town or a city.

01:15:17.360 --> 01:15:22.800
[Guest]: And also, you know, you know, what, what also, you know, so what struck me was how they talk

01:15:22.800 --> 01:15:29.640
[Guest]: about, how they talk about religious freedom, because, you know, they all, almost all of

01:15:29.640 --> 01:15:35.280
[Guest]: them say that there's an extraordinary, as one of, as Pietro Dalla Valle says, an extraordinary

01:15:35.280 --> 01:15:38.640
[Guest]: liberty of conscience in the realm of the Mughal.

01:15:38.640 --> 01:15:40.640
[Guest]: That's a lovely phrase, liberty of conscience.

01:15:40.640 --> 01:15:47.000
[Guest]: It is, and it sounds very, you know, 20th, 21st century, it sounds like, but people,

01:15:47.000 --> 01:15:51.280
[Guest]: anyone is free to practice, not only to practice whatever religion they wish to, but also to

01:15:51.280 --> 01:15:57.840
[Guest]: criticize the other, you know, and these are people who are coming from very sectarian

01:15:57.840 --> 01:16:01.680
[Guest]: Europe where people are killing each other, you know, for, for differences of sect, let

01:16:01.680 --> 01:16:03.080
[Guest]: alone religion.

01:16:03.080 --> 01:16:06.880
[Guest]: And so they're always surprised to see what's going on here.

01:16:06.880 --> 01:16:12.680
[Guest]: But they also, clearly defining it, they also notice this idea of purity that runs through

01:16:12.680 --> 01:16:17.360
[Guest]: the India that they see and, you know, of, of, of castes.

01:16:17.360 --> 01:16:21.920
[Guest]: And so there's a young, there's an Englishman who comes, while Thomas Rowe is here, and

01:16:21.920 --> 01:16:27.440
[Guest]: he has this great idea of building public water supply in Agra.

01:16:27.440 --> 01:16:31.800
[Guest]: And Thomas Rowe is really scathing, and he says, this guy, I mean, and you know, what,

01:16:31.800 --> 01:16:33.120
[Guest]: what kind of stupid plan is this?

01:16:33.120 --> 01:16:37.800
[Guest]: Because nobody will drink water that is not fetched by his own caste.

01:16:37.800 --> 01:16:43.360
[Guest]: You can't have public water flowing like this, because nobody will touch it.

01:16:43.360 --> 01:16:52.520
[Guest]: And Pietro della Valle, in fact, is in his, his sort of expat community, are so fascinated

01:16:52.520 --> 01:16:58.760
[Guest]: by this idea of pure and impure touch that they improvise a little drinking game where,

01:16:58.760 --> 01:17:04.080
[Guest]: you know, everyone is to drink their wine in the Indian fashion without touching the,

01:17:04.080 --> 01:17:05.880
[Guest]: the cup to the lip.

01:17:05.880 --> 01:17:12.120
[Guest]: And whoever spills it then loses, I suppose.

01:17:12.120 --> 01:17:18.720
[Guest]: So, so you get, one of the things that you get actually from, from Jahangir, and it was,

01:17:18.720 --> 01:17:24.720
[Guest]: it was to me really surprisingly vivid image was, you know, he's, he's also traveling in

01:17:24.720 --> 01:17:35.160
[Guest]: Gujarat and he says the roads are lined with these sort of waste level shelves, you know,

01:17:35.160 --> 01:17:40.120
[Guest]: and, and he says that they're there, so because porters, because there's so much trade, so

01:17:40.120 --> 01:17:47.160
[Guest]: porters can rest their load on that shelf without having to take off the load from their

01:17:47.160 --> 01:17:48.160
[Guest]: back.

01:17:48.160 --> 01:17:58.000
[Guest]: It seemed like a very clever and considerate idea, you know, so, so, so yeah, so there

01:17:58.000 --> 01:17:59.000
[Guest]: is this,

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:05.320
[Amit Varma]: In fact, when I, you know, read your book and read this bit about Gujarat and the porters

01:18:05.320 --> 01:18:09.680
[Amit Varma]: relieving themselves, I was reminded of a tweet a few months back, I forget by whom,

01:18:09.680 --> 01:18:15.040
[Amit Varma]: I vaguely seem to think it's one of the journalists who works at the Hindu, but I'm not very sure.

01:18:15.040 --> 01:18:21.120
[Amit Varma]: But the tweet basically had a picture of this big shelf like thing somewhere in Tamil Nadu,

01:18:21.120 --> 01:18:23.040
[Amit Varma]: and saying, do you know what this is for?

01:18:23.040 --> 01:18:26.520
[Amit Varma]: And no one in the area, no one's really seem to have an idea what it was for.

01:18:26.520 --> 01:18:31.080
[Amit Varma]: And the purpose was for laborer women who are carrying things on their head, they can

01:18:31.080 --> 01:18:32.080
[Amit Varma]: rest it there.

01:18:32.080 --> 01:18:35.120
[Amit Varma]: So it's at a slightly higher height than these shelves would be.

01:18:35.120 --> 01:18:40.080
[Amit Varma]: And because no one does that anymore, thankfully, we have progressed beyond that.

01:18:40.080 --> 01:18:41.360
[Amit Varma]: No one knows what these things are.

01:18:41.360 --> 01:18:46.560
[Amit Varma]: They're like artifacts, like, you know, like, like a trivial Stonehenge, in a sense, what

01:18:46.560 --> 01:18:48.080
[Amit Varma]: is this for?

01:18:48.080 --> 01:18:50.120
[Amit Varma]: But now we know what that's for.

01:18:50.120 --> 01:18:55.600
[Amit Varma]: And just knowing what it's for also gives you an image of sort, what kind of life must

01:18:55.600 --> 01:18:59.800
[Amit Varma]: have been like, you know, you were mentioning sort of religious freedoms and all that.

01:18:59.800 --> 01:19:04.280
[Amit Varma]: And of course, your book has a section on how, for example, the Mughals attitude towards

01:19:04.280 --> 01:19:10.160
[Amit Varma]: sati, which is that they disapproved of it, but they didn't want to outlaw it entirely.

01:19:10.160 --> 01:19:14.440
[Amit Varma]: So the instruction that Jahangir gave to his governors was that you talk to the woman concerned

01:19:14.440 --> 01:19:19.240
[Amit Varma]: in every case, offer her inducements, tell her we'll give her a pension or look after

01:19:19.240 --> 01:19:20.240
[Amit Varma]: her.

01:19:20.240 --> 01:19:22.880
[Amit Varma]: And only when you're absolutely sure is of her own free will, then what do you do?

01:19:22.880 --> 01:19:25.680
[Amit Varma]: You have to let it kind of proceed.

01:19:25.680 --> 01:19:32.080
[Amit Varma]: But religion also brings me to the circumstances of his rebellion and eventually taking over.

01:19:32.080 --> 01:19:36.480
[Amit Varma]: The rebellion, of course, is very funny in the sense Akbar sends, Murad is dead by now,

01:19:36.480 --> 01:19:37.480
[Amit Varma]: I think.

01:19:37.480 --> 01:19:40.360
[Amit Varma]: So Danyal is looking after Allahabad.

01:19:40.360 --> 01:19:46.040
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned how Akbar sends him to the Deccan, which is this constant sort of humorous

01:19:46.040 --> 01:19:49.240
[Amit Varma]: leitmotif of this.

01:19:49.240 --> 01:19:52.640
[Amit Varma]: And he sends him to Deccan and Danyal is messing up there.

01:19:52.640 --> 01:19:54.840
[Amit Varma]: So Akbar goes after him.

01:19:54.840 --> 01:19:59.200
[Amit Varma]: And at this point, Jahangir is sent on another campaign with Man Singh.

01:19:59.200 --> 01:20:03.480
[Amit Varma]: But Man Singh has an emergency in Bengal where he is governor, so he leaves.

01:20:03.480 --> 01:20:08.320
[Amit Varma]: And Prince Salim, as he then is surrounded by his hangers on decides to make a play for

01:20:08.320 --> 01:20:10.160
[Amit Varma]: power, takes his army to Agra.

01:20:10.160 --> 01:20:11.160
[Amit Varma]: What happens next?

01:20:11.160 --> 01:20:17.000
[Guest]: Takes his army to Agra and is confronted by the wife, Kilij Khan.

01:20:17.000 --> 01:20:23.080
[Guest]: Poor man, unenviable position because he has to hold and Jahangir and Salim's idea is to

01:20:23.080 --> 01:20:24.760
[Guest]: raid the treasury.

01:20:24.760 --> 01:20:33.080
[Guest]: So Kilij Khan has to keep Akbar's treasury safe while also not losing his own head to

01:20:33.080 --> 01:20:37.560
[Guest]: Jahangir's well-known temper.

01:20:37.560 --> 01:20:44.280
[Guest]: So which he is doing, he's negotiating and saying, standing firm, not letting Jahangir

01:20:44.280 --> 01:20:45.280
[Guest]: in.

01:20:45.280 --> 01:20:50.120
[Guest]: But who knows how things would have gone except luckily for Kilij Khan, Jahangir's grandmother,

01:20:50.120 --> 01:20:52.120
[Guest]: Hamida Bhanu Begum, hears about this.

01:20:52.120 --> 01:20:56.560
[Guest]: And she happens to be in Agra and she's just very shocked and dismayed.

01:20:56.560 --> 01:20:58.920
[Guest]: And she sends word to say, what are you doing?

01:20:58.920 --> 01:21:00.520
[Guest]: And I'm coming to see you.

01:21:00.520 --> 01:21:06.920
[Guest]: And Jahangir is so embarrassed at this idea and doesn't want to, can't face his grandmother.

01:21:06.920 --> 01:21:14.080
[Guest]: So he quickly gets on a boat and sails off to Allahabad, which is luckily vacant since

01:21:14.080 --> 01:21:18.120
[Amit Varma]: Danyal is gone.

01:21:18.120 --> 01:21:24.080
[Amit Varma]: And the sort of the interesting political economy angle behind Jahangir eventually winning

01:21:24.080 --> 01:21:28.680
[Amit Varma]: the succession battle against Khosrow also was that, you know, Man Singh and Aziz Khoka

01:21:28.680 --> 01:21:31.200
[Amit Varma]: of course supported Khosrow, as you said earlier.

01:21:31.200 --> 01:21:35.200
[Amit Varma]: But the mistake they made, and we can only say it's a mistake in retrospect, is that

01:21:35.200 --> 01:21:39.520
[Amit Varma]: rather than just announce him emperor and then try to, you know, work around that, they

01:21:39.520 --> 01:21:44.640
[Amit Varma]: order sort of a council of statesmen and elders to decide on the issue.

01:21:44.640 --> 01:21:52.600
[Amit Varma]: And their powerful faction of a powerful Sunni faction supports Salim and eventually he ascends

01:21:52.600 --> 01:21:54.080
[Amit Varma]: to the throne.

01:21:54.080 --> 01:21:57.720
[Amit Varma]: How much like what is the interplay happening here?

01:21:57.720 --> 01:22:03.080
[Amit Varma]: Are these sort of traditional Sunni figures pissed off at Akbar because of, you know,

01:22:03.080 --> 01:22:08.960
[Amit Varma]: all of Akbar's syncretic secularizing sort of activities and they're like, no, we must

01:22:08.960 --> 01:22:13.240
[Amit Varma]: preserve our faith and that, you know, and Khosrow is Akbar's chosen one.

01:22:13.240 --> 01:22:15.240
[Amit Varma]: So we will go for Salim.

01:22:15.240 --> 01:22:19.240
[Amit Varma]: Is that, is religion an angle in all of this?

01:22:19.240 --> 01:22:22.160
[Guest]: Religion is certainly an angle in all of this.

01:22:22.160 --> 01:22:31.080
[Guest]: Akbar has pissed off the conservative, particularly the Sunni Muslims in and around his court,

01:22:31.080 --> 01:22:38.720
[Guest]: because he has, of course, for his many heresies, he has proclaimed a whole new religion, forget.

01:22:38.720 --> 01:22:43.360
[Guest]: So he's, you know, see the rumors about that he has forsaken Islam, that he's not Muslim

01:22:43.360 --> 01:22:45.840
[Guest]: anymore.

01:22:45.840 --> 01:22:52.280
[Guest]: And so people are, and he's taken away not just that, but he's also taken away power

01:22:52.280 --> 01:23:01.320
[Guest]: from the clerics, you know, who had a great deal of power in the previous courts.

01:23:01.320 --> 01:23:04.720
[Guest]: So they're not happy and Jahangir is very much playing to this gallery.

01:23:04.720 --> 01:23:09.520
[Guest]: So while he's sitting in Allahabad, holding his rebel court, he's also issuing, you know,

01:23:09.520 --> 01:23:14.080
[Guest]: fatwas once in a while saying that my father, what he's doing is very bad, very bad and

01:23:14.080 --> 01:23:18.960
[Guest]: clearly indicating that he will not do this when he becomes emperor.

01:23:18.960 --> 01:23:20.600
[Guest]: So he does have that.

01:23:20.600 --> 01:23:22.760
[Guest]: He does have that support.

01:23:22.760 --> 01:23:32.280
[Guest]: And but that said, it's, you know, things get very, so, so, so I know if you don't mind,

01:23:32.280 --> 01:23:37.480
[Guest]: I'll give you a slightly tangential answer or digressing.

01:23:37.480 --> 01:23:41.160
[Guest]: But you know, it's interesting to me, one of the things I thought while sort of writing

01:23:41.160 --> 01:23:48.080
[Guest]: and thinking about this book, I mean, we think of the Mughals particularly, you know, I mean,

01:23:48.080 --> 01:23:53.440
[Guest]: all historical characters, as we know them, perhaps because we have so many or perhaps

01:23:53.440 --> 01:23:58.120
[Guest]: because of the way that we have understood our own history are thought of in sort of

01:23:58.120 --> 01:24:01.200
[Guest]: black and white bullet point terms, you know.

01:24:01.200 --> 01:24:06.760
[Guest]: And with the Mughals, that black and white bullet point tends to focus on this sort of

01:24:06.760 --> 01:24:12.640
[Guest]: secularism and communalism, you know, and therefore, the greatest amount of writing,

01:24:12.640 --> 01:24:19.680
[Guest]: thinking, debating goes on about this, you know, supposedly secular hero, that is Akbar

01:24:19.680 --> 01:24:23.040
[Guest]: and this communal villain who is Aurangzeb.

01:24:23.040 --> 01:24:27.960
[Guest]: And regardless of whether, you know, secular or communal are words that even make any sense

01:24:27.960 --> 01:24:32.240
[Guest]: in the, you know, in the 16th and 17th centuries, this is how we understand them.

01:24:32.240 --> 01:24:36.840
[Guest]: And even if we are trying to sort of rethink those categories, it's difficult to get out

01:24:36.840 --> 01:24:40.920
[Guest]: of that trap, you know, either you're saying, oh, no, he was secular, no, he wasn't or secular

01:24:40.920 --> 01:24:41.920
[Guest]: is not the right word.

01:24:41.920 --> 01:24:46.800
[Guest]: But somehow those words have to, you know, he was or was not communal, but those words

01:24:46.800 --> 01:24:47.800
[Amit Varma]: keep coming.

01:24:47.800 --> 01:24:52.360
[Amit Varma]: And just thinking about, doesn't this tendency of thinking in these stark binaries carry

01:24:52.360 --> 01:24:56.720
[Amit Varma]: on to the present day where we talk of Nehru or Ambedkar or Gandhi, or even Savarkar, who

01:24:56.720 --> 01:25:01.360
[Amit Varma]: are all deeply complex figures and you know, cannot be pinned down into black and white.

01:25:01.360 --> 01:25:06.840
[Amit Varma]: And that's how people make sense of the world and which is why we need historians.

01:25:06.840 --> 01:25:11.560
[Guest]: And that possibly ties into the great man theory too, you know, when either, you know,

01:25:11.560 --> 01:25:17.040
[Guest]: the great men of history are either great, greatly good or greatly bad.

01:25:17.040 --> 01:25:20.920
[Guest]: And that's how they you know, that's how we understand them.

01:25:20.920 --> 01:25:26.280
[Guest]: But the interesting thing and the nice thing about Jahangir is because he has no, nobody

01:25:26.280 --> 01:25:28.480
[Guest]: is thinking of him as a great man of any kind.

01:25:28.480 --> 01:25:32.680
[Guest]: And so he doesn't have this kind of, there's no pressure, you know.

01:25:32.680 --> 01:25:38.920
[Guest]: So when you read his life, you can read it with a lot more detachment and see how he

01:25:38.920 --> 01:25:42.840
[Guest]: wasn't just this or that, but he was this and also this and also this and also this

01:25:42.840 --> 01:25:46.600
[Guest]: and also this, you know, all kinds of things.

01:25:46.600 --> 01:25:52.640
[Guest]: So I guess one of the things, I mean, post Khosrow's rebellion, but because of it, early

01:25:52.640 --> 01:25:56.320
[Guest]: on in his career is one of the, I suppose if you were thinking of Jahangir in purely

01:25:56.320 --> 01:26:03.600
[Guest]: religious terms, one big blot on his career would be the execution of Guru Arjan Dev.

01:26:03.600 --> 01:26:08.920
[Guest]: But once you start looking at it, you know, that story yields many kinds of possible interpretations.

01:26:08.920 --> 01:26:13.000
[Guest]: And so one, of course, is that Jahangir talks about it again in the Jahangir Nama, it's

01:26:13.000 --> 01:26:14.080
[Guest]: quite clear.

01:26:14.080 --> 01:26:17.920
[Guest]: And there isn't any hint of there being any religious angle to it.

01:26:17.920 --> 01:26:22.800
[Guest]: I mean, until then, Guru Arjan Dev and the Gurus and the Mughals had fairly decent relationship.

01:26:22.800 --> 01:26:30.160
[Guest]: Guru Arjan Dev himself specifically and Akbar had met and got along and Akbar had given

01:26:30.160 --> 01:26:32.880
[Guest]: him a grant and enjoyed talking to him and all that.

01:26:32.880 --> 01:26:38.280
[Guest]: And perhaps because of this reason, Khosrow, when he rebelled, he was on his way to Lahore

01:26:38.280 --> 01:26:44.760
[Guest]: and on the way he stopped at the Guru's hermitage and the Guru blessed him and maybe he gave

01:26:44.760 --> 01:26:47.920
[Guest]: him some money, it's not entirely clear.

01:26:47.920 --> 01:26:53.520
[Guest]: And later on, Jahangir finds out about this and he has him, he says, I had his property

01:26:53.520 --> 01:26:57.200
[Guest]: confiscated and I had him executed.

01:26:57.200 --> 01:27:02.960
[Guest]: But it doesn't seem at all as if this was anything more than a political act.

01:27:02.960 --> 01:27:09.440
[Guest]: On the other hand, it's also possible that Jahangir was in some ways goaded to do this

01:27:09.440 --> 01:27:18.640
[Guest]: by his advisors who would amongst them, number some of these Sunni clerics who would have

01:27:18.640 --> 01:27:24.840
[Guest]: by, because by this time, Sikhism had sort of evolving as a religion and the Guru was

01:27:24.840 --> 01:27:27.480
[Guest]: attracting more and more followers, both Hindus and Muslims.

01:27:27.480 --> 01:27:30.720
[Guest]: And thereby being a political threat as well as much as.

01:27:30.720 --> 01:27:31.720
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly.

01:27:31.720 --> 01:27:37.000
[Guest]: Being a political and a religious threat to his, to Jahangir's mullahs, not to Jahangir

01:27:37.000 --> 01:27:38.000
[Guest]: himself.

01:27:38.000 --> 01:27:41.920
[Guest]: So it's possible, you know, that that was also happening.

01:27:41.920 --> 01:27:50.320
[Guest]: And there's another story, not of another religious man who dies because of Jahangir.

01:27:50.320 --> 01:27:51.320
[Unknown]: Shustri.

01:27:51.320 --> 01:27:52.320
[Guest]: Yeah, Shustri.

01:27:52.320 --> 01:27:53.320
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:27:53.320 --> 01:27:58.480
[Guest]: And I really like this story because he's, you know, so he's a Shia and he's an old man

01:27:58.480 --> 01:27:59.480
[Guest]: by this time.

01:27:59.480 --> 01:28:04.040
[Guest]: And at some point, about 1610 or so, Jahangir has him whipped.

01:28:04.040 --> 01:28:09.120
[Guest]: And then he, soon after he dies, most likely as a consequence.

01:28:09.120 --> 01:28:13.000
[Guest]: And there's this chap called Sajjad Rizvi who has a fantastic essay on all the wheels

01:28:13.000 --> 01:28:17.040
[Guest]: within wheels within wheels that are going on here, you know, and it so, so, so Rizvi

01:28:17.040 --> 01:28:24.120
[Guest]: says that it's possible that Shustri was pretending not to be Shia because of this sort of growing

01:28:24.120 --> 01:28:25.680
[Guest]: Sunni influence in the court.

01:28:25.680 --> 01:28:30.680
[Guest]: It was, he thought it was a good idea to do that.

01:28:30.680 --> 01:28:37.360
[Guest]: And Jahangir has him whipped, not because he is Shia, but because he is pretending not

01:28:37.360 --> 01:28:38.360
[Guest]: to be.

01:28:38.360 --> 01:28:43.960
[Guest]: And by that pretence, he is casting an aspersion on Jahangir's liberality.

01:28:43.960 --> 01:28:47.960
[Guest]: And Jahangir says also that he's making me look like a coarse and bigoted man.

01:28:47.960 --> 01:28:52.160
[Guest]: And you know, how dare he cast this aspersion of bigotry on me.

01:28:52.160 --> 01:28:59.040
[Guest]: And yet, you know, this Sajjad Rizvi goes on that it's also quite possible that it was

01:28:59.040 --> 01:29:04.240
[Guest]: that sectarian Sunni court that had it in for this old, poor old Shia man.

01:29:04.240 --> 01:29:09.440
[Guest]: And again, sort of arm twisted the emperor into having him whipped.

01:29:09.440 --> 01:29:16.960
[Guest]: But Jahangir could not admit this because in his own sense of himself, there is no,

01:29:16.960 --> 01:29:24.000
[Guest]: there is forget bigotry or tolerance, there is very little religious sense.

01:29:24.000 --> 01:29:25.880
[Guest]: And Thomas Rowe puts it very well.

01:29:25.880 --> 01:29:31.160
[Guest]: You know, Thomas Rowe says that he has been bred up without any religion.

01:29:31.160 --> 01:29:35.080
[Guest]: And it was easy for me also to identify.

01:29:35.080 --> 01:29:39.520
[Guest]: I think that, you know, there are many people who, so I have, you know, my father's Hindu,

01:29:39.520 --> 01:29:41.760
[Guest]: my mother is Sikh, neither was particularly religious.

01:29:41.760 --> 01:29:45.440
[Guest]: So, you know, when you're brought up without any kind of religion, you know, I know what

01:29:45.440 --> 01:29:47.720
[Guest]: that, you know, what that means.

01:29:47.720 --> 01:29:49.480
[Guest]: And then Thomas Rowe continues that.

01:29:49.480 --> 01:29:54.120
[Guest]: So therefore, he's either the easiest man to convert or the most difficult because he

01:29:54.120 --> 01:29:59.120
[Guest]: is willing to listen to everything, but he won't believe anything.

01:29:59.120 --> 01:30:05.840
[Guest]: You know, he doesn't have that, that ability to have religious faith, you know, so he's

01:30:05.840 --> 01:30:10.120
[Guest]: He'll watch the stripes of the zebra.

01:30:10.120 --> 01:30:13.040
[Amit Varma]: Yes, yes, exactly.

01:30:13.040 --> 01:30:17.520
[Amit Varma]: The Shusuri story was so mind blowing because, you know, when I heard about it, and from

01:30:17.520 --> 01:30:25.360
[Amit Varma]: you, it was because it is almost rashmonic in its multiple points of views and its multiple

01:30:25.360 --> 01:30:28.640
[Amit Varma]: pretenses that are at the surface level.

01:30:28.640 --> 01:30:34.640
[Amit Varma]: Jahangir's claim is that I don't care whether he's Shia or Sunni, but the fact that he pretended

01:30:34.640 --> 01:30:39.400
[Amit Varma]: was an affront to my liberalism and therefore that pretence deserves the punishment of death.

01:30:39.400 --> 01:30:44.640
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, you point out the possibility that it was under pressure from the Sunnis.

01:30:44.640 --> 01:30:49.680
[Amit Varma]: So he's pretending to be loyal to the Sunni faction who he needs for political reasons.

01:30:49.680 --> 01:30:53.480
[Amit Varma]: And on the other hand, there is that he then needs to pretend perhaps to himself, perhaps

01:30:53.480 --> 01:30:57.240
[Amit Varma]: to the world, that this is not the reason that he actually is liberal.

01:30:57.240 --> 01:30:59.080
[Amit Varma]: So it's layers within layers.

01:30:59.080 --> 01:31:03.440
[Amit Varma]: And it seems like, you know, if there's an Indian Kurosawa, this is such an incredible,

01:31:03.440 --> 01:31:08.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, your book is full of incredible subjects of the sort for novels or films or whatever.

01:31:08.600 --> 01:31:11.960
[Amit Varma]: It's just fairly mind boggling to me.

01:31:11.960 --> 01:31:18.120
[Amit Varma]: But you know, another interesting aspect of his sort of religious leanings and his sort

01:31:18.120 --> 01:31:22.520
[Amit Varma]: of experiments is this interesting guy called Jadrub Ghusain.

01:31:22.520 --> 01:31:23.520
[Amit Varma]: Who is Jadrub Ghusain?

01:31:23.520 --> 01:31:24.840
[Guest]: He's not a Muslim.

01:31:24.840 --> 01:31:29.040
[Guest]: So Jadrub Ghusain is very much not a Muslim.

01:31:29.040 --> 01:31:35.680
[Guest]: He's a very, he's a sort of a Brahmin saint and ascetic.

01:31:35.680 --> 01:31:38.120
[Guest]: And Akbar first finds him.

01:31:38.120 --> 01:31:41.080
[Guest]: And then Jahangir goes to visit him.

01:31:41.080 --> 01:31:45.480
[Guest]: Next he meets him in a cave near Ujjain.

01:31:45.480 --> 01:31:51.480
[Guest]: And Jahangir is just amazed by his asceticism and, you know, his frugality.

01:31:51.480 --> 01:31:57.200
[Guest]: And he, you know, he eats like three mouthfuls a day and he lives his entire life inside

01:31:57.200 --> 01:31:58.360
[Guest]: this tiny little cave.

01:31:58.360 --> 01:32:03.600
[Guest]: And Jahangir has it measured, of course, it's barely possible for a man to get inside.

01:32:03.600 --> 01:32:05.960
[Guest]: And Jahangir goes to meet him and he meets him in private.

01:32:05.960 --> 01:32:11.440
[Guest]: There's even a painting of that shows, you know, the Jadrub Ghusain and Jahangir talking

01:32:11.440 --> 01:32:17.040
[Guest]: outside the cave and all the nobility very much on the fringes of that painting.

01:32:17.040 --> 01:32:20.680
[Guest]: And he does this more than once in the Jahangir Nama.

01:32:20.680 --> 01:32:27.080
[Guest]: And he meets him and he has very long, very detailed and clearly fulfilling conversations

01:32:27.080 --> 01:32:31.960
[Guest]: because he says, you know, after one of them, he says that, you know, I was very happy to

01:32:31.960 --> 01:32:35.920
[Guest]: meet him and I was very sad to depart from him.

01:32:35.920 --> 01:32:41.040
[Guest]: And clearly this man also had some influence over Jahangir because there's an essay, I'm

01:32:41.040 --> 01:32:48.120
[Guest]: forgetting, I think maybe Shirin Musfi has written this essay about how at some point,

01:32:48.120 --> 01:32:54.080
[Guest]: you know, poor Khosrow is in jail or in captivity, but occasionally he's allowed more freedom

01:32:54.080 --> 01:32:56.120
[Guest]: than at other times, you know.

01:32:56.120 --> 01:33:02.120
[Guest]: So at some point you hear in Jahangir Nama, he says that I let Khosrow come to meet me

01:33:02.120 --> 01:33:03.120
[Guest]: every day.

01:33:03.120 --> 01:33:08.120
[Guest]: And it seems that it may have been that, you know, Khosrow's father-in-law, Aziz Koka,

01:33:08.120 --> 01:33:12.720
[Guest]: went to Jadrub Ghusain and said, you know, could you please intercede on his behalf and

01:33:12.720 --> 01:33:15.520
[Guest]: let him move around a little.

01:33:15.520 --> 01:33:18.760
[Guest]: So he had, you know, he had that kind of influence on Jahangir.

01:33:18.760 --> 01:33:25.120
[Guest]: And this idea of asceticism itself seems to have been something that attracted him.

01:33:25.120 --> 01:33:29.400
[Guest]: In fact, there's even a painting of him where he's like a bear chested and you know, sitting

01:33:29.400 --> 01:33:30.400
[Guest]: with...

01:33:30.400 --> 01:33:34.280
[Guest]: Wearing a dhoti and sitting in this sort of ascetic pose.

01:33:34.280 --> 01:33:39.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, I'm just thinking aloud and I could be completely wrong, but it seems

01:33:39.400 --> 01:33:45.480
[Amit Varma]: to me just listening to both what you've said about his sort of religious quest, as it were,

01:33:45.480 --> 01:33:50.700
[Amit Varma]: and also his curiosity about the natural world, such as dog biting the elephant.

01:33:50.700 --> 01:33:57.040
[Amit Varma]: It seems to me that the curiosity itself is intense and genuine, but the quest is kind

01:33:57.040 --> 01:34:02.680
[Amit Varma]: of shallow and that's not necessarily his fault because he is also limited by the tools

01:34:02.680 --> 01:34:03.680
[Amit Varma]: at his disposal.

01:34:03.680 --> 01:34:08.200
[Amit Varma]: While you can say that for someone like Akbar, for example, in the context of religion, it

01:34:08.200 --> 01:34:13.640
[Amit Varma]: would seem that the, you know, both the impulse and the quest itself was deep and genuine.

01:34:13.640 --> 01:34:17.160
[Amit Varma]: You know, he's actually going and meeting Arjun Dev and chatting with him.

01:34:17.160 --> 01:34:19.440
[Amit Varma]: He's writing up to the Dine Elahi.

01:34:19.440 --> 01:34:24.640
[Amit Varma]: And for Jahangir, it's like he just falls short in both those areas.

01:34:24.640 --> 01:34:25.640
[Guest]: Does that make sense?

01:34:25.640 --> 01:34:31.880
[Guest]: That it could, but also here I have to admit to my own inability, you know, one inability

01:34:31.880 --> 01:34:37.760
[Guest]: of not being a historian and therefore not being, I mean, I don't have the languages,

01:34:37.760 --> 01:34:38.760
[Guest]: I have just English.

01:34:38.760 --> 01:34:42.360
[Guest]: So I can't read in Persian, I can't read in other languages.

01:34:42.360 --> 01:34:49.760
[Guest]: And there is this text called Majlis-e-Jahangiri, which records some years of Jahangir's evening

01:34:49.760 --> 01:34:50.760
[Guest]: conversations.

01:34:50.760 --> 01:34:55.920
[Guest]: You know, it's interesting because I think it is Asfar Moin perhaps who pointed this

01:34:55.920 --> 01:35:02.560
[Guest]: out that, you know, I mean, many people say that, for example, in the Jahangir Nama, there

01:35:02.560 --> 01:35:05.160
[Guest]: is no mention of Thomas Rowe.

01:35:05.160 --> 01:35:10.200
[Guest]: And that can be taken as a mark of how insignificant Thomas Rowe was.

01:35:10.200 --> 01:35:15.960
[Guest]: But it's also possible, this is what Moin I think says, that in the Jahangir Nama, Jahangir

01:35:15.960 --> 01:35:21.280
[Guest]: is writing about his days, but not about his nights.

01:35:21.280 --> 01:35:25.640
[Guest]: The evenings are when he has these conversations with people, both the spiritual religious

01:35:25.640 --> 01:35:29.640
[Guest]: conversations and the conversation with ambassadors and visitors and all that.

01:35:29.640 --> 01:35:35.680
[Guest]: And some of that is, I mean, it's not recorded by him, but there is this record by another

01:35:35.680 --> 01:35:41.640
[Guest]: visitor to his court who records some of these religious conversations that he has with various

01:35:41.640 --> 01:35:45.560
[Guest]: clerics and priests who come to his court.

01:35:45.560 --> 01:35:52.400
[Guest]: So, now I don't know, you know, only that I've only been able to, it's not been translated.

01:35:52.400 --> 01:35:56.720
[Guest]: So I've only seen a little bit here and there quoted in essays, but it's possible that that

01:35:56.720 --> 01:36:06.320
[Guest]: reveals a deeper quest, I mean, you know, or at least a deeper interest in these matters.

01:36:06.320 --> 01:36:12.280
[Guest]: He does, you know, he does, it seems, you know, so Akbar has this idea of Sulaykul,

01:36:12.280 --> 01:36:15.920
[Guest]: the peace for all, which becomes a kind of motto for his reign.

01:36:15.920 --> 01:36:21.640
[Guest]: And Jahangir, according to little extracts from this book, describes himself as Mazar-e-Kul,

01:36:21.640 --> 01:36:24.760
[Guest]: which translates as a sort of universal manifestation.

01:36:24.760 --> 01:36:32.560
[Guest]: He says that even the way that God takes care of all his slaves, so I take care of all God's

01:36:32.560 --> 01:36:38.760
[Guest]: slaves, you know, through his own idea of what religion means, of what it means to rule

01:36:38.760 --> 01:36:42.440
[Guest]: over different religions.

01:36:42.440 --> 01:36:48.640
[Guest]: I don't know how deep or sophisticated they were, but they perhaps are more than we can

01:36:48.640 --> 01:36:51.040
[Amit Varma]: gather only from the Jahangir.

01:36:51.040 --> 01:36:54.480
[Amit Varma]: And his instinct seemed to be fairly liberal, as we would call it today.

01:36:54.480 --> 01:36:59.000
[Guest]: Oh, so Thomas Rowe has this, there's a little bit in Thomas Rowe where he talks about how

01:36:59.000 --> 01:37:07.280
[Guest]: he, you know, at some point, Jahangir is in his gups, and he starts talking about liberality

01:37:07.280 --> 01:37:11.480
[Guest]: towards all religions, and Thomas Rowe says he sort of starts crying, because he's so

01:37:11.480 --> 01:37:17.200
[Unknown]: moved by his own good intentions.

01:37:17.200 --> 01:37:25.680
[Guest]: So yes, that idea, certainly, and you know, because he is the product himself of so much

01:37:25.680 --> 01:37:32.440
[Guest]: intermingling, you know, he is, he has a Hindu mother, he has a Hindu mother, he has lived

01:37:32.440 --> 01:37:40.920
[Guest]: his entire life in Hindustan, you know, he this is his country and, and to me the, you

01:37:40.920 --> 01:37:45.640
[Guest]: know, the most telling thing is his taste in food, you know, so you have, you have Babar

01:37:45.640 --> 01:37:51.240
[Guest]: who comes here, and he, for the very few years that he's here, he's really missing his melons,

01:37:51.240 --> 01:37:57.000
[Guest]: he even literally cries when a shipment of melons arrives in Agra from Kabul, he can't

01:37:57.000 --> 01:37:58.000
[Amit Varma]: believe it.

01:37:58.000 --> 01:38:02.280
[Amit Varma]: And modern nationalists would find more reason to dislike Babar because he also says bad

01:38:02.280 --> 01:38:03.280
[Amit Varma]: things about mangoes.

01:38:03.280 --> 01:38:04.280
[Guest]: He says mangoes are okay, okay.

01:38:04.280 --> 01:38:05.280
[Guest]: He says they're a do, but they're nowhere near.

01:38:05.280 --> 01:38:06.280
[Guest]: They're not melons.

01:38:06.280 --> 01:38:07.280
[Guest]: They're not melons.

01:38:07.280 --> 01:38:16.280
[Guest]: And then Jahangir at the beginning of his journey goes to Kabul and almost like it's

01:38:16.280 --> 01:38:19.880
[Guest]: like a mirror effect, you know, he says almost exactly the opposite.

01:38:19.880 --> 01:38:24.080
[Guest]: He says that all the fruits are very nice in Kabul, he has some cherries, he has some

01:38:24.080 --> 01:38:28.480
[Guest]: peaches, he has apricots, melons, you know, he says fruits are all very well, but he says

01:38:28.480 --> 01:38:31.840
[Guest]: nothing can match a mango.

01:38:31.840 --> 01:38:33.160
[Amit Varma]: And this is this is really interesting.

01:38:33.160 --> 01:38:36.320
[Amit Varma]: And actually, you know, question I was saving for the end of the episode, but I'll ask you

01:38:36.320 --> 01:38:42.520
[Amit Varma]: now is this gradual journey where what is essentially a Timurid dynasty, a Timurid people,

01:38:42.520 --> 01:38:46.760
[Amit Varma]: they bring their languages with them, their, you know, their harems and all the women and

01:38:46.760 --> 01:38:51.360
[Amit Varma]: whatever and, and gradually what happens is that one, they get more and more Hindu because

01:38:51.360 --> 01:38:55.680
[Amit Varma]: if you think about it, Jahangir is half Hindu, and his sons even more than that, because

01:38:55.680 --> 01:38:59.880
[Amit Varma]: some of his wives are, you know, Rajput princesses or whatever.

01:38:59.880 --> 01:39:04.560
[Amit Varma]: And not only are they in terms of their bloodline and so on getting more and more Hindu and

01:39:04.560 --> 01:39:09.640
[Amit Varma]: more and more Indian rather, but even culturally, they're losing those old languages, they're

01:39:09.640 --> 01:39:13.720
[Amit Varma]: losing those sort of old ways.

01:39:13.720 --> 01:39:19.160
[Amit Varma]: And it would seem that it's, you know, around this time that you know, that Jahangir that

01:39:19.160 --> 01:39:24.160
[Amit Varma]: line is drawn that they are now an Indian dynasty that the past is behind them that

01:39:24.160 --> 01:39:29.960
[Guest]: you know, wherever they came from Uzbekistan or whatever, it's in the past.

01:39:29.960 --> 01:39:35.760
[Guest]: Yeah, this idea that you know, one day we will conquer Samarkand remains, I think, certainly

01:39:35.760 --> 01:39:41.360
[Guest]: all the way up to Aurangzeb, but it remains really as an idea, you know, that lip service,

01:39:41.360 --> 01:39:47.200
[Guest]: although they try, I think there's some disastrous campaign that Aurangzeb is sent off on by

01:39:47.200 --> 01:39:48.200
[Guest]: Shah Jahan.

01:39:48.200 --> 01:39:51.400
[Guest]: But it's not, I mean, for Babur, that was it.

01:39:51.400 --> 01:39:55.080
[Guest]: That was all he wanted was to be king of Samarkand.

01:39:55.080 --> 01:39:59.440
[Guest]: That was home and that was his ultimate ambition.

01:39:59.440 --> 01:40:03.440
[Guest]: You know, that was Timur's capital and that was what he wanted to be.

01:40:03.440 --> 01:40:07.960
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I was just reminded by another TIL moment which quizzers would like which I got

01:40:07.960 --> 01:40:11.600
[Amit Varma]: from your book, which is about the origin of the word wilayat.

01:40:11.600 --> 01:40:16.240
[Amit Varma]: And you point out how, you know, the term originally means home.

01:40:16.240 --> 01:40:22.480
[Amit Varma]: And it was, you know, Jahangir said it of Kabul or Jahangir said it of Kabul and he

01:40:22.480 --> 01:40:23.880
[Amit Varma]: meant it as home.

01:40:23.880 --> 01:40:26.360
[Guest]: But over time, it has come to mean the opposite.

01:40:26.360 --> 01:40:27.360
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly.

01:40:27.360 --> 01:40:29.480
[Guest]: I was also quite taken aback by that.

01:40:29.480 --> 01:40:33.960
[Guest]: It meant sort of homeland or the land of the, you know, ancestors.

01:40:33.960 --> 01:40:36.760
[Guest]: And it's the meaning is completely turned around.

01:40:36.760 --> 01:40:39.120
[Amit Varma]: And it kind of depends on who you like.

01:40:39.120 --> 01:40:44.560
[Amit Varma]: For example, if an Englishman uses it off England, he is talking of England as his wilayat,

01:40:44.560 --> 01:40:45.560
[Amit Varma]: his home.

01:40:45.560 --> 01:40:49.320
[Amit Varma]: But then when an Indian starts calling it wilayat, picking up from him, the meaning

01:40:49.320 --> 01:40:52.000
[Guest]: changes and somehow that new meaning.

01:40:52.000 --> 01:40:53.000
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:40:53.000 --> 01:40:54.560
[Amit Varma]: The real meaning.

01:40:54.560 --> 01:40:58.800
[Amit Varma]: And that was just, you know, so, so fascinating to me.

01:40:58.800 --> 01:41:02.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's the kind of the really fast.

01:41:02.000 --> 01:41:06.600
[Amit Varma]: One thing I learned recently about the Mughals and it's really fascinated me and I did an

01:41:06.600 --> 01:41:11.240
[Amit Varma]: episode on Ira Moukhati with it on her excellent book Daughters of the Sun.

01:41:11.240 --> 01:41:15.920
[Amit Varma]: It's about the women, the Mughal women, and even in your book, there is a very prominent

01:41:15.920 --> 01:41:21.800
[Amit Varma]: role played by the women starting with Hamida Banu Bekum, of course, Akbar's mother, Humayun's

01:41:21.800 --> 01:41:28.160
[Amit Varma]: bride from Afghanistan, who is, you know, who Jahangir is so scared of that when she

01:41:28.160 --> 01:41:32.920
[Amit Varma]: says, I'm coming to see what the hell you are doing, trying to rob the treasury, he

01:41:32.920 --> 01:41:35.440
[Amit Varma]: runs off to Allahabad.

01:41:35.440 --> 01:41:40.400
[Amit Varma]: And later, one of the sort of things that really struck me about the legendary Nur Jahan

01:41:40.400 --> 01:41:45.520
[Amit Varma]: is that, again, you've pointed out that being an emperor, Jahangir could have any woman

01:41:45.520 --> 01:41:46.880
[Amit Varma]: he wanted.

01:41:46.880 --> 01:41:51.480
[Amit Varma]: And what he chose, who he fell in love with and stayed so loyal with and build this enduring

01:41:51.480 --> 01:41:56.960
[Amit Varma]: friendship and partnership with was a widow in her mid 30s.

01:41:56.960 --> 01:42:05.080
[Amit Varma]: And this whole attitude towards women, the way they revere and respect the women, you

01:42:05.080 --> 01:42:08.160
[Amit Varma]: know, in their palaces and how much they listen to them.

01:42:08.160 --> 01:42:10.440
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that.

01:42:10.440 --> 01:42:17.840
[Guest]: So, I mean, I think, you know, the more I read about the Mughals and their sort of extended

01:42:17.840 --> 01:42:24.880
[Guest]: families, more sort of these very strong women come out, you know, they're just they're all

01:42:24.880 --> 01:42:25.880
[Guest]: over the place.

01:42:25.880 --> 01:42:33.520
[Guest]: Babur, you know, in his Baburnama, writes about his grandmother as being one of the

01:42:33.520 --> 01:42:38.840
[Guest]: most important influences on his life and not just, you know, as grandmother, but also

01:42:38.840 --> 01:42:42.520
[Guest]: as actually advisor on military matters and strategic matters.

01:42:42.520 --> 01:42:44.520
[Guest]: Because he's 12 and he's taking over.

01:42:44.520 --> 01:42:45.520
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:42:45.520 --> 01:42:50.360
[Guest]: And he goes to her and she advises him on what to do and how to do it.

01:42:50.360 --> 01:42:55.920
[Guest]: So and his sister, Khanzada, is very much, I think, in fact, Ira talks about it in her

01:42:55.920 --> 01:43:00.880
[Guest]: book, there's a painting she has in her book in which Khanzada is part of a council, you

01:43:00.880 --> 01:43:05.920
[Guest]: know, and she's I think she's she's the biggest figure in that council.

01:43:05.920 --> 01:43:11.000
[Guest]: She's clearly the most important person in that in that council.

01:43:11.000 --> 01:43:12.800
[Guest]: Then there are, you know, there's some there are others.

01:43:12.800 --> 01:43:18.720
[Guest]: There's the Salima Sultan Begum, who's Bayram Khan's wife and later Akbar's wife, then Gulbadan

01:43:18.720 --> 01:43:21.400
[Guest]: Begum, who is Akbar's aunt.

01:43:21.400 --> 01:43:26.080
[Guest]: And all of these people play a very strong, important role in Jahangir's life.

01:43:26.080 --> 01:43:32.200
[Guest]: There's also Hamida Banu is only one of Humayun's wives and Humayun has at least three who are,

01:43:32.200 --> 01:43:40.040
[Guest]: you know, that's fairly rare for three wives to sort of remain known in history for fairly

01:43:40.040 --> 01:43:41.040
[Guest]: big accomplishments.

01:43:41.040 --> 01:43:47.320
[Guest]: One is, you know, the Haji Begum, his first wife, she builds the Humayun's tomb.

01:43:47.320 --> 01:43:52.560
[Guest]: Then there's, you know, Hamida Banu, who, you know, first resists his overtures for

01:43:52.560 --> 01:43:57.680
[Guest]: 40 days, 40 days it takes of him wooing her.

01:43:57.680 --> 01:44:04.640
[Guest]: And one of his stepmothers finally persuades Hamida Banu with that eternal argument that

01:44:04.640 --> 01:44:08.280
[Guest]: has been used to persuade, you know, women to marry.

01:44:08.280 --> 01:44:10.600
[Guest]: She says that, you know, you have to marry someone.

01:44:10.600 --> 01:44:13.760
[Guest]: So why not him as well as anyone else?

01:44:13.760 --> 01:44:16.320
[Amit Varma]: And he's a fugitive right now, mind you, not an emperor.

01:44:16.320 --> 01:44:20.960
[Amit Varma]: I think Shersaas Shatori is basically ruling what we call India at this time.

01:44:20.960 --> 01:44:27.400
[Guest]: So, there is a fairly bad state and the state will become much worse very soon.

01:44:27.400 --> 01:44:33.040
[Guest]: So his third wife, Mahachuchak Begum, who is youngest, sorry, youngest wife, who is

01:44:33.040 --> 01:44:39.000
[Guest]: also the mother of Akbar's young half-brother, Muhammad Hakim, and is the de facto ruler

01:44:39.000 --> 01:44:47.960
[Guest]: of Kabul and, you know, battles when Akbar sends one of his governors there, she throws

01:44:47.960 --> 01:44:55.280
[Guest]: him out and goes to battle with him and defeats him, you know.

01:44:55.280 --> 01:45:03.560
[Guest]: So there are many examples of very, very strong women in the life of Jahangir and Jahangir

01:45:03.560 --> 01:45:09.360
[Guest]: himself is indebted to at least three of them, this, you know, Hamida Banu, his grandmother,

01:45:09.360 --> 01:45:16.000
[Guest]: Salima Sultan and Gulbadan Begum for interceding with Akbar on his behalf, you know, keeping

01:45:16.000 --> 01:45:24.760
[Guest]: the relationship at least somewhat civil on sort of more or less working terms so that,

01:45:24.760 --> 01:45:27.480
[Guest]: you know, it doesn't become completely ineligible.

01:45:27.480 --> 01:45:32.320
[Amit Varma]: And as you pointed out, the later intercede with Jahangir on Khosrow's behalf.

01:45:32.320 --> 01:45:35.560
[Guest]: No, but they do on behalf of Mirza Aziz Khoka.

01:45:35.560 --> 01:45:39.960
[Guest]: So Jahangir wants to, he's, you know, always had a thing in it because Mirza Aziz has supported

01:45:39.960 --> 01:45:40.960
[Guest]: Khosrow.

01:45:40.960 --> 01:45:41.960
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:45:41.960 --> 01:45:51.480
[Guest]: And so when he gets his opportunity, he wants to certainly put him in prison, possibly worse.

01:45:51.480 --> 01:45:59.640
[Guest]: But the women are listening from behind the screen and they call out and they stop him.

01:45:59.640 --> 01:46:04.120
[Guest]: So yeah, so they have an influence on and thereafter, you know, Nur Jahan, she becomes

01:46:04.120 --> 01:46:06.080
[Guest]: as powerful as she does.

01:46:06.080 --> 01:46:08.200
[Guest]: And it's exceptional, but it doesn't happen in a vacuum.

01:46:08.200 --> 01:46:11.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, there's enough precedent for powerful women.

01:46:11.920 --> 01:46:17.840
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that, you know, even Nur Jahan's origin story is kind of, you know,

01:46:17.840 --> 01:46:23.040
[Amit Varma]: interesting how she was again, not an Indian per se, not like one of the other Rajput princesses.

01:46:23.040 --> 01:46:25.520
[Amit Varma]: And tell me a little bit about that.

01:46:25.520 --> 01:46:30.440
[Guest]: So she comes fleeing from Persia with her, no, she doesn't come, sorry, her parents come

01:46:30.440 --> 01:46:32.080
[Guest]: fleeing from Persia.

01:46:32.080 --> 01:46:36.040
[Guest]: She is born en route in Kandahar.

01:46:36.040 --> 01:46:42.840
[Guest]: And then, so there is this, what is called the abandonment narrative and the abandonment

01:46:42.840 --> 01:46:49.960
[Guest]: of Nur Jahan that, you know, they have, her mother delivers her, but they are poor, they

01:46:49.960 --> 01:46:52.800
[Guest]: are in, it's a difficult journey.

01:46:52.800 --> 01:46:56.320
[Guest]: They don't have any, they don't know how they'll be able to take care of her.

01:46:56.320 --> 01:46:59.080
[Guest]: So they leave her under a tree.

01:46:59.080 --> 01:47:04.360
[Guest]: But they only walked a little while before, you know, my parents decide this is not, they

01:47:04.360 --> 01:47:05.360
[Guest]: can't do this.

01:47:05.360 --> 01:47:11.440
[Guest]: So her father goes back and he finds her with, you know, sort of a black snake wrapped around

01:47:11.440 --> 01:47:14.680
[Guest]: her or, you know, some variations on that theme.

01:47:14.680 --> 01:47:21.120
[Guest]: And then picks her up and brings her to Agra.

01:47:21.120 --> 01:47:26.000
[Guest]: But this is not, I mean, this is not a story that, this is a little, you know, sort of

01:47:26.000 --> 01:47:27.880
[Guest]: a sort of myth making of Nur Jahan.

01:47:27.880 --> 01:47:30.000
[Guest]: There's no such story told.

01:47:30.000 --> 01:47:33.240
[Guest]: I mean, Jahangir certainly doesn't tell it.

01:47:33.240 --> 01:47:36.760
[Guest]: So, but whatever it is, they came, they were refugees.

01:47:36.760 --> 01:47:41.840
[Guest]: There were many refugees coming in from Persia at the time.

01:47:41.840 --> 01:47:48.000
[Guest]: And they found employment in Akbar's court, her father, he asked big.

01:47:48.000 --> 01:47:53.400
[Guest]: And then, I mean, he's doing fairly okay, but nothing spectacular.

01:47:53.400 --> 01:47:57.360
[Guest]: And under Jahangir, his career is arrested for quite a while.

01:47:57.360 --> 01:47:59.480
[Guest]: He is himself arrested, in fact.

01:47:59.480 --> 01:48:05.840
[Guest]: And his son is, one of his sons is arrested and killed for being part of Khosrow's gang.

01:48:05.840 --> 01:48:07.440
[Amit Varma]: Khosrow's second rebellion.

01:48:07.440 --> 01:48:08.440
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:48:08.440 --> 01:48:11.680
[Guest]: So, so things are not looking very good for them.

01:48:11.680 --> 01:48:21.720
[Guest]: And then in 1611, so six years after he becomes emperor, Jahangir marries Nur Jahan.

01:48:21.720 --> 01:48:29.720
[Guest]: And then suddenly, you know, the fortune of the Agyasbeg family just goes through the

01:48:29.720 --> 01:48:30.720
[Amit Varma]: roof.

01:48:30.720 --> 01:48:34.240
[Amit Varma]: I mean, they all become incredibly powerful.

01:48:34.240 --> 01:48:37.720
[Amit Varma]: And Nur Jahan is almost co-ruling with him in a sense.

01:48:37.720 --> 01:48:43.360
[Amit Varma]: In fact, a common criticism, which you point out may have been motivated by Shah Jahan's

01:48:43.360 --> 01:48:47.880
[Amit Varma]: sort of trying to rationalize his rebelling against Nur Jahan.

01:48:47.880 --> 01:48:50.240
[Amit Varma]: And the king was sort of, oh, he wasn't really governing.

01:48:50.240 --> 01:48:51.240
[Amit Varma]: He was a weak emperor.

01:48:51.240 --> 01:48:52.600
[Amit Varma]: Nur Jahan did all the governing.

01:48:52.600 --> 01:48:55.840
[Amit Varma]: So a real man had to come and get the job done.

01:48:55.840 --> 01:49:03.160
[Amit Varma]: And the actual probable thing is that Jahangir was egoless in the sense of he was doing what

01:49:03.160 --> 01:49:05.560
[Amit Varma]: was, he was sharing power with her.

01:49:05.560 --> 01:49:10.020
[Amit Varma]: And by all accounts, they had a very close friendship as well.

01:49:10.020 --> 01:49:13.240
[Amit Varma]: And he was sharing power with her because it was a practical thing to do that left him

01:49:13.240 --> 01:49:20.360
[Amit Varma]: to hunt and to drink and do the sort of things that he kind of enjoyed.

01:49:20.360 --> 01:49:24.720
[Amit Varma]: What also intrigued me was the sort of political games, like on the one hand, Khurram, the

01:49:24.720 --> 01:49:27.720
[Amit Varma]: later Shah Jahan is married to her niece.

01:49:27.720 --> 01:49:32.480
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, she then tries to get her daughter from her first marriage married

01:49:32.480 --> 01:49:33.480
[Amit Varma]: to Khosrow.

01:49:33.480 --> 01:49:39.120
[Amit Varma]: But Khosrow refuses allegedly, but Khurram anyway has Khosrow killed later.

01:49:39.120 --> 01:49:43.200
[Amit Varma]: And that daughter ends up marrying the youngest brother, Sheryar.

01:49:43.200 --> 01:49:46.200
[Amit Varma]: And Sheryar becomes a contender to the throne.

01:49:46.200 --> 01:49:51.480
[Amit Varma]: But then eventually when, you know, and after Jahangir for a very brief while, Khosrow's

01:49:51.480 --> 01:49:54.200
[Amit Varma]: son is sort of told that you are the king.

01:49:54.200 --> 01:49:57.560
[Amit Varma]: And then Shah Jahan just has all of them knocked off.

01:49:57.560 --> 01:49:59.080
[Guest]: It's a bloodbath.

01:49:59.080 --> 01:50:05.520
[Guest]: It reminded me of you know, that that last scene, that last montage in the Godfather,

01:50:05.520 --> 01:50:11.600
[Guest]: you know, when one after the other, all the competition is being is just shot through

01:50:11.600 --> 01:50:12.600
[Amit Varma]: the head.

01:50:12.600 --> 01:50:19.400
[Amit Varma]: He just wipes them out, but his son is Aurangzeb, so karma is on the way.

01:50:19.400 --> 01:50:24.520
[Amit Varma]: But tell me also a little bit about like when most people think of Jahangir and thanks perhaps

01:50:24.520 --> 01:50:27.960
[Amit Varma]: to Bollywood and Mughlai Azam, they think of Salim and Anarkali.

01:50:27.960 --> 01:50:28.960
[Amit Varma]: Did Anarkali exist?

01:50:28.960 --> 01:50:34.120
[Guest]: So there's no, I mean, I just feel very bad every time I have to say this, because I found

01:50:34.120 --> 01:50:40.040
[Guest]: people I didn't realize until after I wrote this book and started talking to people how

01:50:40.040 --> 01:50:46.520
[Guest]: fond people are of the story of Anarkali and Salim and how much, how people don't at all

01:50:46.520 --> 01:50:49.000
[Guest]: like being told that she didn't exist.

01:50:49.000 --> 01:50:57.200
[Guest]: Though, I mean, you know, I like, I mean, there's no particular evidence for her having

01:50:57.200 --> 01:51:03.320
[Guest]: existed, except that there's this diary entry by a chap called William Finch, who's one

01:51:03.320 --> 01:51:06.340
[Guest]: of those early East India Company traders.

01:51:06.340 --> 01:51:14.120
[Guest]: And he goes here, again, he goes to Lahore and he says there's this tomb and the tomb

01:51:14.120 --> 01:51:20.800
[Guest]: is of Imam Kali, translated as pomegranate blossom.

01:51:20.800 --> 01:51:26.840
[Guest]: And she was, she was the Akbar's wife and Daniyal's mother.

01:51:26.840 --> 01:51:31.980
[Guest]: And Shah Salim had a quote unquote to do with her.

01:51:31.980 --> 01:51:37.760
[Guest]: So it's not at all the sort of epic romance that we have in Mughal-e-Azam, it's much more

01:51:37.760 --> 01:51:41.080
[Guest]: sordid story that he tells.

01:51:41.080 --> 01:51:42.080
[Guest]: But tomb is there.

01:51:42.080 --> 01:51:48.080
[Guest]: I think the, I think the archaeological survey has offices there or something, there's a

01:51:48.080 --> 01:51:51.240
[Guest]: sort of government office in that tomb.

01:51:51.240 --> 01:51:58.400
[Guest]: From what I've read, it is said to be the tomb of one of Jahangir's wives, but not Anarkali,

01:51:58.400 --> 01:52:03.480
[Guest]: but Sahib Jamal, who was the mother of his second son, Parvez.

01:52:03.480 --> 01:52:11.400
[Guest]: Also, like it seemed to me that if she had existed and if, I mean, the story as it's

01:52:11.400 --> 01:52:16.240
[Guest]: told, certainly as a story as it's told in Mughal-e-Azam does not hold water in the context

01:52:16.240 --> 01:52:22.720
[Guest]: of, you know, Mughal family life, because class would certainly not have been an issue.

01:52:22.720 --> 01:52:28.360
[Guest]: You know, if Jahangir could have as many concubines as he wanted, nobody would stop him.

01:52:28.360 --> 01:52:31.360
[Guest]: And marry whoever he wanted.

01:52:31.360 --> 01:52:35.720
[Guest]: In fact, there is an instance of him wanting to marry somebody that Akbar doesn't approve

01:52:35.720 --> 01:52:41.280
[Guest]: of, you know, because he wants to marry Zayn Khan's, a nobleman's daughter or niece, and

01:52:41.280 --> 01:52:42.960
[Guest]: he's already married to her niece and daughter.

01:52:42.960 --> 01:52:46.520
[Guest]: So Akbar doesn't like this idea of, you know, marrying two women who are so closely related

01:52:46.520 --> 01:52:47.520
[Guest]: to each other.

01:52:47.520 --> 01:52:54.680
[Guest]: But Jahangir insists and eventually, you know, Akbar gives in and that's it.

01:52:54.680 --> 01:52:59.160
[Guest]: There's no, you know, it doesn't become some huge issue.

01:52:59.160 --> 01:53:03.880
[Guest]: So for all these reasons, it seemed to me that it wasn't, I don't find it particularly

01:53:03.880 --> 01:53:09.120
[Guest]: credible, but, you know, who knows, maybe we'll discover something later.

01:53:09.120 --> 01:53:15.680
[Guest]: But also I think what at some point, you know, you know, the stories that, I guess, you know,

01:53:15.680 --> 01:53:21.160
[Guest]: when you're writing any book or any story, or even whether it's history or not, there

01:53:21.160 --> 01:53:25.920
[Guest]: are certain stories you are more attracted to or want to tell more than others.

01:53:25.920 --> 01:53:32.760
[Guest]: So I thought, you know, this idea of this young love fighting parental opposition is

01:53:32.760 --> 01:53:36.360
[Guest]: a very nice story, but it has been told so many times.

01:53:36.360 --> 01:53:42.240
[Guest]: And for me, the more interesting story, even if that Anarkali story is true, for me, the

01:53:42.240 --> 01:53:45.000
[Guest]: more interesting story is the Noor Jeha Jahangir story.

01:53:45.000 --> 01:53:51.760
[Guest]: You know, this, this, these, these two people who meet very much in their middle age, you

01:53:51.760 --> 01:53:56.280
[Guest]: know, by even by today's standards, let alone those times, she's in her 30s, he's in his

01:53:56.280 --> 01:53:57.280
[Guest]: 40s.

01:53:57.280 --> 01:53:59.680
[Guest]: They have both been married before, not just...

01:53:59.680 --> 01:54:02.760
[Amit Varma]: Kindly watch your words by today's standards, 40 is very young.

01:54:02.760 --> 01:54:06.160
[Guest]: 40 is very young, I know.

01:54:06.160 --> 01:54:07.160
[Guest]: It's the new 30.

01:54:07.160 --> 01:54:10.160
[Guest]: 40 is the new late 20s.

01:54:10.160 --> 01:54:19.520
[Guest]: So I just turned 22.

01:54:19.520 --> 01:54:24.720
[Guest]: So yeah, so, so this idea of, you know, I mean, he's, of course, been married, he's

01:54:24.720 --> 01:54:29.920
[Guest]: much married, but she also is not, you know, she's not, she's her second marriage, too.

01:54:29.920 --> 01:54:34.080
[Guest]: She already has a child by her first marriage.

01:54:34.080 --> 01:54:35.840
[Guest]: They don't have any children together.

01:54:35.840 --> 01:54:36.840
[Guest]: He never married again.

01:54:36.840 --> 01:54:38.880
[Guest]: After that, she's his last wife.

01:54:38.880 --> 01:54:45.120
[Guest]: They seem to share a relationship of some degree of equality, some degree of mutual

01:54:45.120 --> 01:54:46.120
[Guest]: respect.

01:54:46.120 --> 01:54:47.120
[Guest]: They clearly have similar interests.

01:54:47.120 --> 01:54:50.400
[Guest]: You know, I mean, he is addicted to hunting.

01:54:50.400 --> 01:54:51.760
[Amit Varma]: We've already started.

01:54:51.760 --> 01:54:53.080
[Amit Varma]: She's supposed to be a really good shot.

01:54:53.080 --> 01:54:55.000
[Guest]: She's supposed to be a really good shot.

01:54:55.000 --> 01:54:56.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:54:56.000 --> 01:55:02.520
[Guest]: And you know, he has an interest in sort of jewelry and clothes and beauty.

01:55:02.520 --> 01:55:06.320
[Guest]: So does she, you know, she's sort of that.

01:55:06.320 --> 01:55:15.280
[Guest]: The tomb of her father, Itimad-ud-Daulah's tomb in Agra is really a really gorgeous little

01:55:15.280 --> 01:55:16.280
[Guest]: monument.

01:55:16.280 --> 01:55:21.120
[Guest]: So they have both have a very finely developed aesthetic sense.

01:55:21.120 --> 01:55:27.800
[Guest]: They both enjoy, you know, feasting and partying and traveling, you know, they travel together

01:55:27.800 --> 01:55:29.160
[Guest]: up and down the country.

01:55:29.160 --> 01:55:35.280
[Amit Varma]: There's a very nice anecdote in your book about the lights of the city going off because,

01:55:35.280 --> 01:55:38.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, they're coming back from somewhere together in a bullock cart.

01:55:38.200 --> 01:55:42.840
[Amit Varma]: He's riding a bullock cart and she's by his side and his people feel the emperor should

01:55:42.840 --> 01:55:44.680
[Amit Varma]: not be seen like this.

01:55:44.680 --> 01:55:47.640
[Amit Varma]: But it's just a couple enjoying a really nice moment.

01:55:47.640 --> 01:55:50.600
[Guest]: No, no, not the emperor not be seen like this.

01:55:50.600 --> 01:55:55.360
[Guest]: So they've put off the lights because, so to keep her in purdah, because she's out,

01:55:55.360 --> 01:55:57.600
[Guest]: she's sitting with him.

01:55:57.600 --> 01:56:00.320
[Amit Varma]: So she's not, she's not, she's not.

01:56:00.320 --> 01:56:03.400
[Amit Varma]: The absence of light as a purdah of sorts.

01:56:03.400 --> 01:56:07.680
[Guest]: So the absence of light as purdah and this, you know, he's commanded a bullock cart from

01:56:07.680 --> 01:56:09.280
[Guest]: somewhere and the two of them are riding.

01:56:09.280 --> 01:56:11.400
[Guest]: I thought it's a lovely image.

01:56:11.400 --> 01:56:18.520
[Guest]: And yeah, to me it captures something of their, something of the sort of carefree, that kind

01:56:18.520 --> 01:56:24.160
[Guest]: of carefree love or carefree affection, which I think comes later in life.

01:56:24.160 --> 01:56:27.960
[Guest]: You know, young passion is not, is not carefree in that way.

01:56:27.960 --> 01:56:33.480
[Amit Varma]: This is a mature, settled love and it doesn't even seem to be so say affected by like, you

01:56:33.480 --> 01:56:37.440
[Amit Varma]: know, we know power corrupts, power corrupts the road, people, especially the massive power

01:56:37.440 --> 01:56:39.280
[Amit Varma]: that a Mughal emperor must have.

01:56:39.280 --> 01:56:41.840
[Amit Varma]: But this seems to be quite removed from all of that.

01:56:41.840 --> 01:56:43.880
[Guest]: It's just genuine affection.

01:56:43.880 --> 01:56:44.880
[Guest]: It comes across.

01:56:44.880 --> 01:56:51.120
[Guest]: And so that was the story that I liked that story better.

01:56:51.120 --> 01:56:55.960
[Guest]: And so that was the one that I was more interested in, in English.

01:56:55.960 --> 01:56:57.440
[Amit Varma]: That's a very powerful story.

01:56:57.440 --> 01:56:59.800
[Amit Varma]: We've already spoken for more than a couple of hours.

01:56:59.800 --> 01:57:00.800
[Amit Varma]: Tell me something.

01:57:00.800 --> 01:57:05.760
[Amit Varma]: I see sort of four kind of divergent trends.

01:57:05.760 --> 01:57:10.560
[Amit Varma]: And one trend is, of course, that history is used more and more these days as a political

01:57:10.560 --> 01:57:11.560
[Amit Varma]: tool.

01:57:11.560 --> 01:57:17.200
[Amit Varma]: It's simplified and you know, so you'll paint historical figures in either black or white

01:57:17.200 --> 01:57:22.960
[Amit Varma]: and use it to suit your narrative purposes, whatever they might be, which indicates that

01:57:22.960 --> 01:57:27.840
[Amit Varma]: simplistic narratives, maybe another illustration of this is the romance between the alleged

01:57:27.840 --> 01:57:31.560
[Amit Varma]: and arcane and jungi that simplistic narratives have an appeal to us.

01:57:31.560 --> 01:57:32.560
[Amit Varma]: We can all get it.

01:57:32.560 --> 01:57:35.960
[Amit Varma]: Our mind is not a mind resist complexities.

01:57:35.960 --> 01:57:42.120
[Amit Varma]: But yet I see in modern times in the last two or three decades in the rest of the world

01:57:42.120 --> 01:57:46.560
[Amit Varma]: and maybe now over here with people like you and Manu Pillay and Ira Makhoti and Anna Safi

01:57:46.560 --> 01:57:51.720
[Amit Varma]: coming along, that there is also this readership developing this hunger developing for popular

01:57:51.720 --> 01:57:54.720
[Amit Varma]: history where people just love these stories.

01:57:54.720 --> 01:57:59.080
[Amit Varma]: They can take the complexity, you know, they are not choosing simple binaries.

01:57:59.080 --> 01:58:04.560
[Amit Varma]: There is a hunger for these and part of these I have mused in the past is perhaps because

01:58:04.560 --> 01:58:05.840
[Amit Varma]: we love stories.

01:58:05.840 --> 01:58:07.440
[Amit Varma]: That's how we explain the world to each other.

01:58:07.440 --> 01:58:11.200
[Amit Varma]: And where can you get better stories than in our history, especially India's history

01:58:11.200 --> 01:58:17.420
[Amit Varma]: is just wild and mind boggling and so entertaining.

01:58:17.420 --> 01:58:18.600
[Amit Varma]: And these are two divergent things.

01:58:18.600 --> 01:58:21.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one is history as a political tool being simplified binaries.

01:58:21.960 --> 01:58:25.000
[Amit Varma]: But the other is that people just love history.

01:58:25.000 --> 01:58:26.000
[Amit Varma]: What are your thoughts on this?

01:58:26.000 --> 01:58:32.640
[Guest]: No, I think I think the way you put it is really that's it's true that you know, people

01:58:32.640 --> 01:58:33.640
[Guest]: love history.

01:58:33.640 --> 01:58:40.720
[Guest]: People also like at a certain level, I think in school particularly, you will find, you

01:58:40.720 --> 01:58:47.280
[Guest]: know, that almost near near unanimous agreement that history is just the most boring subject

01:58:47.280 --> 01:58:52.440
[Guest]: and maths is the most incomprehensible, you know, and possibly for similar reasons, because

01:58:52.440 --> 01:58:57.080
[Guest]: they're both taught in these abstract terms that seem to have no relevance to to real

01:58:57.080 --> 01:58:58.080
[Guest]: life.

01:58:58.080 --> 01:59:03.200
[Guest]: You know, those mathematical formulas, I still don't know what it was that I was memorizing

01:59:03.200 --> 01:59:05.080
[Guest]: and to what end.

01:59:05.080 --> 01:59:11.420
[Guest]: And similarly, with, you know, this history and that's what we started off talking.

01:59:11.420 --> 01:59:18.600
[Guest]: And at the same time, it's also you know, in our current political life, excites great

01:59:18.600 --> 01:59:23.040
[Guest]: passions and you know, great anger.

01:59:23.040 --> 01:59:28.000
[Guest]: And so, you know, I don't know if you've read this book that's come out recently called

01:59:28.000 --> 01:59:29.720
[Guest]: Malevolent Republic.

01:59:29.720 --> 01:59:31.640
[Guest]: Of course, by Kapil Kumar.

01:59:31.640 --> 01:59:32.880
[Guest]: I just finished reading it.

01:59:32.880 --> 01:59:35.560
[Guest]: I thought it was very polemical, very compelling.

01:59:35.560 --> 01:59:36.560
[Guest]: I enjoyed it very much.

01:59:36.560 --> 01:59:40.320
[Guest]: I don't know whether I agreed with every part of it, but it was very good.

01:59:40.320 --> 01:59:44.200
[Amit Varma]: There were parts I didn't agree with, but it was extremely thought provoking and so

01:59:44.200 --> 01:59:45.200
[Amit Varma]: well written.

01:59:45.200 --> 01:59:47.960
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, I've asked Kapil to be on my show and he's agreed, but we've never actually

01:59:47.960 --> 01:59:50.840
[Amit Varma]: managed to make, be in the same place at the same time.

01:59:50.840 --> 01:59:52.200
[Amit Varma]: So one day we will make that work.

01:59:52.200 --> 01:59:54.200
[Guest]: I look forward to hearing him talk.

01:59:54.200 --> 01:59:56.200
[Amit Varma]: To continue with your thought.

01:59:56.200 --> 01:59:57.920
[Guest]: So I felt very similar.

01:59:57.920 --> 01:59:59.860
[Guest]: I mean, I enjoyed it very much.

01:59:59.860 --> 02:00:05.960
[Guest]: And he has these asides, if you remember, on history and he and he and he basically

02:00:05.960 --> 02:00:14.400
[Guest]: his argument is that a certain type of nationalist, mostly leftist historian has not been entirely

02:00:14.400 --> 02:00:22.600
[Guest]: accurate about the past, has sort of papered over the sins of, you know, Muslim invaders

02:00:22.600 --> 02:00:28.640
[Guest]: while only attacking European colonizers.

02:00:28.640 --> 02:00:31.440
[Guest]: And I'm not sure if I entirely agree with this.

02:00:31.440 --> 02:00:35.960
[Guest]: You know, there are there are many writings of many sorts on the many, many different

02:00:35.960 --> 02:00:40.880
[Guest]: types of Muslim rulers that India has had.

02:00:40.880 --> 02:00:49.440
[Guest]: But I do I think that that he's right in the sense that there has been a certain sense

02:00:49.440 --> 02:00:54.280
[Guest]: of nation building that has informed the writing of history.

02:00:54.280 --> 02:01:00.080
[Guest]: And it's not surprising, you know, in a postcolonial country when the entire country's every all

02:01:00.080 --> 02:01:05.280
[Guest]: resources are concentrated on keeping the country one.

02:01:05.280 --> 02:01:07.080
[Guest]: So naturally, history also comes into that.

02:01:07.080 --> 02:01:10.680
[Guest]: So that I think perhaps accounts for the fact that, you know, history, the way that we are

02:01:10.680 --> 02:01:17.080
[Guest]: taught it is all, you know, worthy, worthy, not just great men and women, but worthy men

02:01:17.080 --> 02:01:23.840
[Guest]: and women, virtuous men and women who have been virtuously working from, you know, ancient

02:01:23.840 --> 02:01:32.320
[Guest]: times from Buddha onwards, they were all working to make India sort of the nation state that

02:01:32.320 --> 02:01:33.400
[Guest]: it is.

02:01:33.400 --> 02:01:38.040
[Guest]: And the problem with that is, I mean, one, of course, that it turns history into something

02:01:38.040 --> 02:01:42.680
[Guest]: that can be a little boring and, you know, just sort of talking down, kind of a morality

02:01:42.680 --> 02:01:44.400
[Guest]: play more than anything else.

02:01:44.400 --> 02:01:48.920
[Guest]: But also that it can be that it can be flipped, you know, so suddenly, you know, after the

02:01:48.920 --> 02:01:55.880
[Guest]: decades of doing this, the country's sense of itself now depends on what happened in

02:01:55.880 --> 02:01:58.720
[Guest]: the past or how we say what happened in the past.

02:01:58.720 --> 02:02:04.800
[Guest]: So suddenly the country, you know, the nation wants to know why Aurangzeb did this, or,

02:02:04.800 --> 02:02:09.400
[Guest]: you know, how dare he break these temples or what is Tipu Sultan doing in our textbook.

02:02:09.400 --> 02:02:14.560
[Guest]: And so it becomes, there's something sort of disproportionate, you know, the past takes

02:02:14.560 --> 02:02:18.480
[Guest]: on a disproportionate relevance to the present.

02:02:18.480 --> 02:02:23.280
[Guest]: And then from there, of course, it almost way too easily that the present then has to

02:02:23.280 --> 02:02:29.600
[Guest]: be spent writing these supposed wrongs from the past.

02:02:29.600 --> 02:02:34.240
[Amit Varma]: And that doesn't spell very good news for us.

02:02:34.240 --> 02:02:38.200
[Amit Varma]: And I think that comes both from the right and the left.

02:02:38.200 --> 02:02:41.480
[Amit Varma]: My friend, the political commentator Sadanand Dhoomey was on the show a few months ago,

02:02:41.480 --> 02:02:47.360
[Amit Varma]: and he made the very interesting point that whenever he appears on these TV talk shows

02:02:47.360 --> 02:02:53.280
[Amit Varma]: with right-winger supporters of the current dispensation, he finds that they seem to have

02:02:53.280 --> 02:02:58.160
[Amit Varma]: almost this warped sense of time, where what happened yesterday is as relevant as what

02:02:58.160 --> 02:03:00.200
[Amit Varma]: happened in the 1500s.

02:03:00.200 --> 02:03:06.080
[Amit Varma]: And you know, the fact that Babur breaking a mosque can have ripples of repercussion

02:03:06.080 --> 02:03:14.080
[Amit Varma]: through the centuries is both perverse and almost kind of stunning.

02:03:14.080 --> 02:03:17.640
[Amit Varma]: So it's sort of, you know, whenever I end my show, and I'm talking to my guest about

02:03:17.640 --> 02:03:23.520
[Amit Varma]: a particular subject, I'll ask this almost cliched question by now when people on Twitter

02:03:23.520 --> 02:03:28.080
[Amit Varma]: make fun of me for asking it every time, which is what gives you hope and what gives you

02:03:28.080 --> 02:03:30.960
[Amit Varma]: despair about XYZ and so on.

02:03:30.960 --> 02:03:34.960
[Amit Varma]: Given the sort of divergent trends of history, on the one hand, it's a political tool and

02:03:34.960 --> 02:03:40.000
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, perhaps a study of history in many cases is affected by the ideological

02:03:40.000 --> 02:03:42.160
[Amit Varma]: lens that you bring to bear upon it.

02:03:42.160 --> 02:03:44.120
[Amit Varma]: And that's one side of the situation.

02:03:44.120 --> 02:03:49.960
[Amit Varma]: But the other side is that more and more people have access to historical documents and are

02:03:49.960 --> 02:03:56.360
[Amit Varma]: showing greater interest in books of history, you know, such as by people like you, what

02:03:56.360 --> 02:04:03.360
[Amit Varma]: gives you hope and what gives you despair about the study of history over the next few

02:04:03.360 --> 02:04:05.000
[Amit Varma]: years and decades in India?

02:04:05.000 --> 02:04:10.680
[Guest]: So I think exactly these two things that you said, I think, you know, the despair certainly

02:04:10.680 --> 02:04:17.000
[Guest]: comes from the fact that, you know, like you're saying, Sadanand, who may say that, you know,

02:04:17.000 --> 02:04:22.600
[Guest]: it's almost like we are fighting our elections in the 16th century or 17th century.

02:04:22.600 --> 02:04:25.240
[Guest]: You know, those are the burning topics of the day.

02:04:25.240 --> 02:04:30.040
[Guest]: You know, we must have the Mughals be accountable now, demand answers from them.

02:04:30.040 --> 02:04:34.200
[Guest]: And it's a very, it's a clever thing, because, you know, when if you're demanding answers

02:04:34.200 --> 02:04:39.560
[Guest]: from the Mughals, then you don't have time to demand answers from your current rulers

02:04:39.560 --> 02:04:44.520
[Guest]: or current government, you know, all the attention is just over there.

02:04:44.520 --> 02:04:51.440
[Guest]: And even that, you know, today we are talking and I don't know the whole news yet, but that,

02:04:51.440 --> 02:04:55.440
[Guest]: you know, Section 144 should have been imposed on many parts, many cities in the country.

02:04:55.440 --> 02:04:59.560
[Amit Varma]: We are recording this on the day of the Ayodhya judgment, by the way.

02:04:59.560 --> 02:05:00.560
[Guest]: So, yeah.

02:05:00.560 --> 02:05:06.600
[Guest]: And, you know, imagine that too, that these are the kind of debates that we are embroiled

02:05:06.600 --> 02:05:07.960
[Guest]: in.

02:05:07.960 --> 02:05:14.400
[Guest]: And yet at the same time, this very fact that, you know, I find, you know, that one of the

02:05:14.400 --> 02:05:21.000
[Guest]: one of the nicest and most heartening things about writing this book was that whenever

02:05:21.000 --> 02:05:26.640
[Guest]: I've spoken, not just, you know, spoken outside or met people or people who've read it, there's

02:05:26.640 --> 02:05:35.480
[Guest]: been such a huge amount of interest and curiosity that that obviously exists.

02:05:35.480 --> 02:05:41.120
[Guest]: And people, perhaps as a result of this, perhaps because of this kind of, you know, these visceral

02:05:41.120 --> 02:05:45.400
[Guest]: emotional reactions that are sort of taking over our public discourse, perhaps because

02:05:45.400 --> 02:05:50.840
[Guest]: of this, people now want to know what really happened.

02:05:50.840 --> 02:05:56.840
[Guest]: And secondly, you know, people that you meet every day are very happy to enjoy history.

02:05:56.840 --> 02:06:00.720
[Guest]: You know, I mean, I think that's the all these complications and these nuances and all these

02:06:00.720 --> 02:06:06.400
[Guest]: wheels within wheels and stories within stories and all this sort of soap operas of it is

02:06:06.400 --> 02:06:10.680
[Guest]: what makes it so interesting and thrilling and absorbing, you know, because these are

02:06:10.680 --> 02:06:15.480
[Guest]: stories and people want to hear those stories and there's nothing about the complication

02:06:15.480 --> 02:06:17.040
[Guest]: that puts them off.

02:06:17.040 --> 02:06:20.040
[Guest]: In fact, that's what attracts people.

02:06:20.040 --> 02:06:24.480
[Guest]: So and I think the fact that, you know, more and more people are writing this kind of book

02:06:24.480 --> 02:06:31.120
[Guest]: is obviously an answer to sort of a growing demand and that that is definitely a good,

02:06:31.120 --> 02:06:41.040
[Guest]: good, I think, nice, hopeful sign that people are not just willing, but want to sort of

02:06:41.040 --> 02:06:48.080
[Guest]: take a deep dive into into the past and just swim around, you know, looking at the fish

02:06:48.080 --> 02:06:54.320
[Guest]: and the corals, not judging all of it or getting hyper excited about all of it, but just enjoying

02:06:54.320 --> 02:06:55.320
[Amit Varma]: the view.

02:06:55.320 --> 02:06:56.320
[Amit Varma]: No, I couldn't agree with you more.

02:06:56.320 --> 02:07:00.640
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I feel extremely hopeful about the fact that, I mean, I just think the more

02:07:00.640 --> 02:07:06.040
[Amit Varma]: people dive into these stories, as you put about and swim about in these strange waters,

02:07:06.040 --> 02:07:10.560
[Amit Varma]: that they will begin to get rid of the otherness of others.

02:07:10.560 --> 02:07:14.960
[Amit Varma]: And hopefully through, you know, books like you and your writing.

02:07:14.960 --> 02:07:16.440
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much for coming on the show.

